summary.p: Enable or disable the initial animation when a series is displayed. The animation can also be set as a configuration object. Please note that this option only applies to the initial animation of the series itself. For other animations, see chart.animation and the animation parameter under the API methods.The following properties are supported:

dl.dd: The duration of the animation in milliseconds.

When using jQuery as the general framework, the easing can be set to linear orswing. More easing functions are available with the use of jQuery plug-ins, most notablythe jQuery UI suite. See the jQuery docs. When using MooTools as the general framework, use the property name transition instead of easing.

summary.p: Due to poor performance, animation is disabled in old IE browsers for column charts and polar charts.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ArearangeSeries.Color
member.summary: The main color of the series. In line type series it applies to the line and the point markers unless otherwise specified. In bar type series it applies to the bars unless a color is specified per point. The default value is pulled from the options.colors array.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ArearangeSeries.Compare
member.summary: Compare the values of the series against the first value in the visible range. The y axis will show percentage or absolute change depending on whether compare is set to "percent" or "value". When this is applied to multiple series, it allows comparing the development of the series against each other.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ArearangeSeries.ConnectNulls
member.summary: Whether to draw a line between points on either side of a null point, or render a gap between them.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ArearangeSeries.CropThreshold
member.summary: When the series contains less points than the crop threshold, all points are drawn, event if the points fall outside the visible plot area at the current zoom. The advantage of drawing all points (including markers and columns), is that animation is performed on updates. On the other hand, when the series contains more points than the crop threshold, the series data is cropped to only contain points that fall within the plot area. The advantage of cropping away invisible points is to increase performance on large series. .

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ArearangeSeries.Cursor
member.summary: You can set the cursor to "pointer" if you have click events attached to the series, to signal to the user that the points and lines can be clicked.

member.summary:
A name for the dash style to use for the graph. Applies only to series type having a graph, like line, spline, area and scatter in case it has a lineWidth. The value for the dashStyle include:
Solid
ShortDash
ShortDot
ShortDashDot
ShortDashDotDot
Dot
Dash
LongDash
DashDot
LongDashDot
LongDashDotDot

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ArearangeSeries.DataLabels
member.summary: Extended data labels for range series types. Range series data labels have no x and y options. Instead, they have xLow, xHigh, yLow and yHigh options to allow the higher and lower data label sets individually.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ArearangeSeries.EnableMouseTracking
member.summary: Enable or disable the mouse tracking for a specific series. This includes point tooltips and click events on graphs and points. When using shared tooltips (default in stock charts), mouse tracking is not required. For large datasets it improves performance.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ArearangeSeries.FillColor
member.summary: Fill color or gradient for the area. When null, the series' color is used with the series' fillOpacity.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ArearangeSeries.FillOpacity
member.summary: Fill opacity for the area. Note that when you set an explicit fillColor, the fillOpacity is not applied. Instead, you should define the opacity in the fillColor with an rgba color definition.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ArearangeSeries.GapSize
member.summary:
Defines when to display a gap in the graph. A gap size of 5 means that if the distance between two points is greater than five times that of the two closest points, the graph will be broken.
In practice, this option is most often used to visualize gaps in time series. In a stock chart, intraday data is available for daytime hours, while gaps will appear in nights and weekends..

summary.p: If no x values are given for the points in a series, pointInterval defines the interval of the x values in milliseconds. For example, if a series contains one value each day, set pointInterval to 24 * 3600 * 1000.
Since Highstock 2.1, it can be combined with pointIntervalUnit to draw irregular intervals.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ArearangeSeries.PointIntervalUnit
member.summary: On datetime series, this allows for setting the pointInterval to the two irregular time units, month and year. Combine it with pointInterval to draw quarters, 6 months, 10 years etc.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ArearangeSeries.StickyTracking
member.summary: Sticky tracking of mouse events. When true, the mouseOut event on a series isn't triggered until the mouse moves over another series, or out of the plot area. When false, the mouseOut event on a series is triggered when the mouse leaves the area around the series' graph or markers. This also implies the tooltip when not shared. When stickyTracking is false, the tooltip will be hidden when moving the mouse between series. Defaults to true for line and area type series, but to false for columns, candlesticks etc.

summary.p: Datetime formats for the header of the tooltip in a stock chart. The format can vary within a chart depending on the currently selected time range and the current data grouping.
The default formats are:

For each of these array definitions, the first item is the format used when the active time span is one unit. For instance, if the current data applies to one week, the first item of the week array is used. The second and third items are used when the active time span is more than two units. For instance, if the current data applies to two weeks, the second and third item of the week array are used, and applied to the start and end date of the time span.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ArearangeSeriesDataGrouping.Enabled
member.summary: Enable or disable data grouping. Defaults to true.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ArearangeSeriesDataGrouping.Forced
member.summary: When data grouping is forced, it runs no matter how small the intervals are. This can be handy for example when the sum should be calculated for values appearing at random times within each hour. Defaults to false.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ArearangeSeriesDataGrouping.GroupPixelWidth
member.summary: The approximate pixel width of each group. If for example a series with 30 points is displayed over a 600 pixel wide plot area, no grouping is performed. If however the series contains so many points that the spacing is less than the groupPixelWidth, Highcharts will try to group it into appropriate groups so that each is more or less two pixels wide. If multiple series with different group pixel widths are drawn on the same x axis, all series will take the greatest width. For example, line series have 2px default group width, while column series have 10px. If combined, both the line and the column will have 10px by default. Defaults to 2.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ArearangeSeriesDataGrouping.Smoothed
member.summary: Normally, a group is indexed by the start of that group, so for example when 30 daily values are grouped into one month, that month's x value will be the 1st of the month. This apparently shifts the data to the left. When the smoothed option is true, this is compensated for. The data is shifted to the middle of the group, and min and max values are preserved. Internally, this is used in the Navigator series. Defaults to false.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ArearangeSeriesDataLabels.Formatter
member.summary:
Callback JavaScript function to format the data label. Note that if a format is defined, the format takes precedence and the formatter is ignored. Available data are:
this.percentage Stacked series and pies only. The point's percentage of the total.
this.point The point object. The point name, if defined, is available through this.point.name.
this.series: The series object. The series name is available through this.series.name.
this.total Stacked series only. The total value at this point's x value.
this.x: The x value.
this.y: The y value.

summary.p: The HTML of the tooltip header line. Variables are enclosed by curly brackets. Available variablesare point.key, series.name, series.color and other members from the point and series objects. The point.key variable contains the category name, x value or datetime string depending on the type of axis. For datetime axes, the point.key date format can be set using tooltip.xDateFormat.
Defaults to {point.key}

The HTML of the point's line in the tooltip. Variables are enclosed by curly brackets. Available variables are point.x, point.y, point.change, series.name and series.color and other properties on the same form. Furthermore, point.y can be extended by the tooltip.valuePrefix and tooltip.valueSuffix variables. This can also be overridden for each series, which makes it a good hook for displaying units.

summary.p: Enable or disable the initial animation when a series is displayed. The animation can also be set as a configuration object. Please note that this option only applies to the initial animation of the series itself. For other animations, see chart.animation and the animation parameter under the API methods.The following properties are supported:

dl.dd: The duration of the animation in milliseconds.

When using jQuery as the general framework, the easing can be set to linear orswing. More easing functions are available with the use of jQuery plug-ins, most notablythe jQuery UI suite. See the jQuery docs. When using MooTools as the general framework, use the property name transition instead of easing.

member.summary: Compare the values of the series against the first value in the visible range. The y axis will show percentage or absolute change depending on whether compare is set to "percent" or "value". When this is applied to multiple series, it allows comparing the development of the series against each other.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreaSeries.ConnectNulls
member.summary: Whether to draw a line between points on either side of a null point, or render a gap between them.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreaSeries.CropThreshold
member.summary: When the series contains less points than the crop threshold, all points are drawn, event if the points fall outside the visible plot area at the current zoom. The advantage of drawing all points (including markers and columns), is that animation is performed on updates. On the other hand, when the series contains more points than the crop threshold, the series data is cropped to only contain points that fall within the plot area. The advantage of cropping away invisible points is to increase performance on large series. .

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreaSeries.GapSize
member.summary:
Defines when to display a gap in the graph. A gap size of 5 means that if the distance between two points is greater than five times that of the two closest points, the graph will be broken.
In practice, this option is most often used to visualize gaps in time series. In a stock chart, intraday data is available for daytime hours, while gaps will appear in nights and weekends..

summary.p: Datetime formats for the header of the tooltip in a stock chart. The format can vary within a chart depending on the currently selected time range and the current data grouping.
The default formats are:

For each of these array definitions, the first item is the format used when the active time span is one unit. For instance, if the current data applies to one week, the first item of the week array is used. The second and third items are used when the active time span is more than two units. For instance, if the current data applies to two weeks, the second and third item of the week array are used, and applied to the start and end date of the time span.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreaSeriesDataGrouping.Enabled
member.summary: Enable or disable data grouping. Defaults to true.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreaSeriesDataGrouping.Forced
member.summary: When data grouping is forced, it runs no matter how small the intervals are. This can be handy for example when the sum should be calculated for values appearing at random times within each hour. Defaults to false.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreaSeriesDataGrouping.GroupPixelWidth
member.summary: The approximate pixel width of each group. If for example a series with 30 points is displayed over a 600 pixel wide plot area, no grouping is performed. If however the series contains so many points that the spacing is less than the groupPixelWidth, Highcharts will try to group it into appropriate groups so that each is more or less two pixels wide. If multiple series with different group pixel widths are drawn on the same x axis, all series will take the greatest width. For example, line series have 2px default group width, while column series have 10px. If combined, both the line and the column will have 10px by default. Defaults to 2.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreaSeriesDataGrouping.Smoothed
member.summary: Normally, a group is indexed by the start of that group, so for example when 30 daily values are grouped into one month, that month's x value will be the 1st of the month. This apparently shifts the data to the left. When the smoothed option is true, this is compensated for. The data is shifted to the middle of the group, and min and max values are preserved. Internally, this is used in the Navigator series. Defaults to false.

member.summary: How many decimals to show for the point.change value when the series.compare option is set. This is overridable in each series' tooltip options object. The default is to preserve all decimals.

summary.p: Whether the tooltip should follow the mouse as it moves across columns, pie slices and other point types with an extent. By default it behaves this way for scatter, bubble and pie series by override in the plotOptions for those series types.
For touch moves to behave the same way, followTouchMove must be true also.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreaSeriesTooltip.FollowTouchMove
member.summary: Whether the tooltip should follow the finger as it moves on a touch device. In order to take effect, chart.zoomType and chart.pinchType must be disabled.

summary.p: The HTML of the tooltip header line. Variables are enclosed by curly brackets. Available variablesare point.key, series.name, series.color and other members from the point and series objects. The point.key variable contains the category name, x value or datetime string depending on the type of axis. For datetime axes, the point.key date format can be set using tooltip.xDateFormat.
Defaults to {point.key}

The HTML of the point's line in the tooltip. Variables are enclosed by curly brackets. Available variables are point.x, point.y, point.change, series.name and series.color and other properties on the same form. Furthermore, point.y can be extended by the tooltip.valuePrefix and tooltip.valueSuffix variables. This can also be overridden for each series, which makes it a good hook for displaying units.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreaSeriesTooltip.PointFormatter
member.summary: A callback function for formatting the HTML output for a single point in the tooltip. Like the pointFormat string, but with more flexibility.

member.summary: Allow this series' points to be selected by clicking on the markers or bars.

summary.p: Enable or disable the initial animation when a series is displayed. The animation can also be set as a configuration object. Please note that this option only applies to the initial animation of the series itself. For other animations, see chart.animation and the animation parameter under the API methods.The following properties are supported:

dl.dd: The duration of the animation in milliseconds.

When using jQuery as the general framework, the easing can be set to linear orswing. More easing functions are available with the use of jQuery plug-ins, most notablythe jQuery UI suite. See the jQuery docs. When using MooTools as the general framework, use the property name transition instead of easing.

summary.p: Due to poor performance, animation is disabled in old IE browsers for column charts and polar charts.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreasplinerangeSeries.Color
member.summary: The main color of the series. In line type series it applies to the line and the point markers unless otherwise specified. In bar type series it applies to the bars unless a color is specified per point. The default value is pulled from the options.colors array.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreasplinerangeSeries.Compare
member.summary: Compare the values of the series against the first value in the visible range. The y axis will show percentage or absolute change depending on whether compare is set to "percent" or "value". When this is applied to multiple series, it allows comparing the development of the series against each other.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreasplinerangeSeries.ConnectNulls
member.summary: Whether to draw a line between points on either side of a null point, or render a gap between them.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreasplinerangeSeries.CropThreshold
member.summary: When the series contains less points than the crop threshold, all points are drawn, event if the points fall outside the visible plot area at the current zoom. The advantage of drawing all points (including markers and columns), is that animation is performed on updates. On the other hand, when the series contains more points than the crop threshold, the series data is cropped to only contain points that fall within the plot area. The advantage of cropping away invisible points is to increase performance on large series. .

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreasplinerangeSeries.Cursor
member.summary: You can set the cursor to "pointer" if you have click events attached to the series, to signal to the user that the points and lines can be clicked.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreasplinerangeSeries.DashStyle
member.summary:
A name for the dash style to use for the graph. Applies only to series type having a graph, like line, spline, area and scatter in case it has a lineWidth. The value for the dashStyle include:
Solid
ShortDash
ShortDot
ShortDashDot
ShortDashDotDot
Dot
Dash
LongDash
DashDot
LongDashDot
LongDashDotDot

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreasplinerangeSeries.DataLabels
member.summary: Extended data labels for range series types. Range series data labels have no x and y options. Instead, they have xLow, xHigh, yLow and yHigh options to allow the higher and lower data label sets individually.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreasplinerangeSeries.EnableMouseTracking
member.summary: Enable or disable the mouse tracking for a specific series. This includes point tooltips and click events on graphs and points. When using shared tooltips (default in stock charts), mouse tracking is not required. For large datasets it improves performance.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreasplinerangeSeries.FillColor
member.summary: Fill color or gradient for the area. When null, the series' color is used with the series' fillOpacity.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreasplinerangeSeries.FillOpacity
member.summary: Fill opacity for the area. Note that when you set an explicit fillColor, the fillOpacity is not applied. Instead, you should define the opacity in the fillColor with an rgba color definition.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreasplinerangeSeries.GapSize
member.summary:
Defines when to display a gap in the graph. A gap size of 5 means that if the distance between two points is greater than five times that of the two closest points, the graph will be broken.
In practice, this option is most often used to visualize gaps in time series. In a stock chart, intraday data is available for daytime hours, while gaps will appear in nights and weekends..

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreasplinerangeSeries.Id
member.summary: An id for the series. This can be used after render time to get a pointer to the series object through chart.get().

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreasplinerangeSeries.Index

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreasplinerangeSeries.Keys
member.summary: An array specifying which option maps to which key in the data point array. This makes it convenient to work with unstructured data arrays from different sources.

summary.p: If no x values are given for the points in a series, pointInterval defines the interval of the x values in milliseconds. For example, if a series contains one value each day, set pointInterval to 24 * 3600 * 1000.
Since Highstock 2.1, it can be combined with pointIntervalUnit to draw irregular intervals.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreasplinerangeSeries.PointIntervalUnit
member.summary: On datetime series, this allows for setting the pointInterval to the two irregular time units, month and year. Combine it with pointInterval to draw quarters, 6 months, 10 years etc.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreasplinerangeSeries.PointRange
member.summary: The width of each point on the x axis. For example in a column chart with one value each day, the pointRange would be 1 day (= 24 * 3600 * 1000 milliseconds). This is normally computed automatically, but this option can be used to override the automatic value.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreasplinerangeSeries.PointStart
member.summary: If no x values are given for the points in a series, pointStart defines on what value to start. On a datetime X axis, the number will be given as milliseconds since 1970-01-01, for example Date.UTC(2011, 0, 1).

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreasplinerangeSeries.StickyTracking
member.summary: Sticky tracking of mouse events. When true, the mouseOut event on a series isn't triggered until the mouse moves over another series, or out of the plot area. When false, the mouseOut event on a series is triggered when the mouse leaves the area around the series' graph or markers. This also implies the tooltip when not shared. summary.p: Datetime formats for the header of the tooltip in a stock chart. The format can vary within a chart depending on the currently selected time range and the current data grouping.
The default formats are:

For each of these array definitions, the first item is the format used when the active time span is one unit. For instance, if the current data applies to one week, the first item of the week array is used. The second and third items are used when the active time span is more than two units. For instance, if the current data applies to two weeks, the second and third item of the week array are used, and applied to the start and end date of the time span.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreasplinerangeSeriesDataGrouping.Enabled
member.summary: Enable or disable data grouping. Defaults to true.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreasplinerangeSeriesDataGrouping.Forced
member.summary: When data grouping is forced, it runs no matter how small the intervals are. This can be handy for example when the sum should be calculated for values appearing at random times within each hour. Defaults to false.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreasplinerangeSeriesDataGrouping.GroupPixelWidth
member.summary: The approximate pixel width of each group. If for example a series with 30 points is displayed over a 600 pixel wide plot area, no grouping is performed. If however the series contains so many points that the spacing is less than the groupPixelWidth, Highcharts will try to group it into appropriate groups so that each is more or less two pixels wide. If multiple series with different group pixel widths are drawn on the same x axis, all series will take the greatest width. For example, line series have 2px default group width, while column series have 10px. If combined, both the line and the column will have 10px by default. Defaults to 2.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreasplinerangeSeriesDataGrouping.Smoothed
member.summary: Normally, a group is indexed by the start of that group, so for example when 30 daily values are grouped into one month, that month's x value will be the 1st of the month. This apparently shifts the data to the left. When the smoothed option is true, this is compensated for. The data is shifted to the middle of the group, and min and max values are preserved. Internally, this is used in the Navigator series. Defaults to false.

member.summary:
Callback JavaScript function to format the data label. Note that if a format is defined, the format takes precedence and the formatter is ignored. Available data are:
this.percentage Stacked series and pies only. The point's percentage of the total.
this.point The point object. The point name, if defined, is available through this.point.name.
this.series: The series object. The series name is available through this.series.name.
this.total Stacked series only. The total value at this point's x value.

summary.p: The HTML of the tooltip header line. Variables are enclosed by curly brackets. Available variablesare point.key, series.name, series.color and other members from the point and series objects. The point.key variable contains the category name, x value or datetime string depending on the type of axis. For datetime axes, the point.key date format can be set using tooltip.xDateFormat.
Defaults to {point.key}

The HTML of the point's line in the tooltip. Variables are enclosed by curly brackets. Available variables are point.x, point.y, point.change, series.name and series.color and other properties on the same form. Furthermore, point.y can be extended by the tooltip.valuePrefix and tooltip.valueSuffix variables. This can also be overridden for each series, which makes it a good hook for displaying units.

summary.p: Enable or disable the initial animation when a series is displayed. The animation can also be set as a configuration object. Please note that this option only applies to the initial animation of the series itself. For other animations, see chart.animation and the animation parameter under the API methods.The following properties are supported:

dl.dd: The duration of the animation in milliseconds.

When using jQuery as the general framework, the easing can be set to linear orswing. More easing functions are available with the use of jQuery plug-ins, most notablythe jQuery UI suite. See the jQuery docs. When using MooTools as the general framework, use the property name transition instead of easing.

member.summary: Compare the values of the series against the first value in the visible range. The y axis will show percentage or absolute change depending on whether compare is set to "percent" or "value". When this is applied to multiple series, it allows comparing the development of the series against each other.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreasplineSeries.ConnectNulls
member.summary: Whether to draw a line between points on either side of a null point, or render a gap between them.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreasplineSeries.CropThreshold
member.summary: When the series contains less points than the crop threshold, all points are drawn, event if the points fall outside the visible plot area at the current zoom. The advantage of drawing all points (including markers and columns), is that animation is performed on updates. On the other hand, when the series contains more points than the crop threshold, the series data is cropped to only contain points that fall within the plot area. The advantage of cropping away invisible points is to increase performance on large series. .

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreasplineSeries.Cursor

member.summary: Enable or disable the mouse tracking for a specific series. This includes point tooltips and click events on graphs and points. When using shared tooltips (default in stock charts), mouse tracking is not required. For large datasets it improves performance.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreasplineSeries.FillOpacity
member.summary: Fill opacity for the area. Note that when you set an explicit fillColor, the fillOpacity is not applied. Instead, you should define the opacity in the fillColor with an rgba color definition.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreasplineSeries.GapSize
member.summary:
Defines when to display a gap in the graph. A gap size of 5 means that if the distance between two points is greater than five times that of the two closest points, the graph will be broken.
In practice, this option is most often used to visualize gaps in time series. In a stock chart, intraday data is available for daytime hours, while gaps will appear in nights and weekends..

summary.p: If no x values are given for the points in a series, pointInterval defines the interval of the x values in milliseconds. For example, if a series contains one value each day, set pointInterval to 24 * 3600 * 1000.
Since Highstock 2.1, it can be combined with pointIntervalUnit to draw irregular intervals.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreasplineSeries.StickyTracking
member.summary: Sticky tracking of mouse events. When true, the mouseOut event on a series isn't triggered until the mouse moves over another series, or out of the plot area. When false, the mouseOut event on a series is triggered when the mouse leaves the area around the series' graph or markers. This also implies the tooltip when not shared. When stickyTracking is false, the tooltip will be hidden when moving the mouse between series. Defaults to true for line and area type series, but to false for columns, candlesticks etc.

summary.p: Datetime formats for the header of the tooltip in a stock chart. The format can vary within a chart depending on the currently selected time range and the current data grouping.
The default formats are:

For each of these array definitions, the first item is the format used when the active time span is one unit. For instance, if the current data applies to one week, the first item of the week array is used. The second and third items are used when the active time span is more than two units. For instance, if the current data applies to two weeks, the second and third item of the week array are used, and applied to the start and end date of the time span.

member.summary: Enable or disable data grouping. Defaults to true.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreasplineSeriesDataGrouping.Forced
member.summary: When data grouping is forced, it runs no matter how small the intervals are. This can be handy for example when the sum should be calculated for values appearing at random times within each hour. Defaults to false.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreasplineSeriesDataGrouping.GroupPixelWidth
member.summary: The approximate pixel width of each group. If for example a series with 30 points is displayed over a 600 pixel wide plot area, no grouping is performed. If however the series contains so many points that the spacing is less than the groupPixelWidth, Highcharts will try to group it into appropriate groups so that each is more or less two pixels wide. If multiple series with different group pixel widths are drawn on the same x axis, all series will take the greatest width. For example, line series have 2px default group width, while column series have 10px. If combined, both the line and the column will have 10px by default. Defaults to 2.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreasplineSeriesDataGrouping.Smoothed
member.summary: Normally, a group is indexed by the start of that group, so for example when 30 daily values are grouped into one month, that month's x value will be the 1st of the month. This apparently shifts the data to the left. When the smoothed option is true, this is compensated for. The data is shifted to the middle of the group, and min and max values are preserved. Internally, this is used in the Navigator series. Defaults to false.

member.summary:
Callback JavaScript function to format the data label. Note that if a format is defined, the format takes precedence and the formatter is ignored. Available data are:
this.percentage Stacked series and pies only. The point's percentage of the total.
this.point The point object. The point name, if defined, is available through this.point.name.
this.series: The series object. The series name is available through this.series.name.
this.total Stacked series only. The total value at this point's x value.
this.x: The x value.
this.y: The y value.

summary.p: A predefined shape or symbol for the marker. When null, the symbol is pulled from options.symbols. Other possible values are "circle", "square", "diamond", "triangle" and "triangle-down".
Additionally, the URL to a graphic can be given on this form: "url(graphic.png)". Note that for the image to be applied to exported charts, its URL needs to be accessible by the export server.
Custom callbacks for symbol path generation can also be added to Highcharts.SVGRenderer.prototype.symbols. The callback is then used by its method name, as shown in the demo.

member.summary: How many decimals to show for the point.change value when the series.compare option is set. This is overridable in each series' tooltip options object. The default is to preserve all decimals.

summary.p: Whether the tooltip should follow the mouse as it moves across columns, pie slices and other point types with an extent. By default it behaves this way for scatter, bubble and pie series by override in the plotOptions for those series types.
For touch moves to behave the same way, followTouchMove must be true also.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.AreasplineSeriesTooltip.FollowTouchMove
member.summary: Whether the tooltip should follow the finger as it moves on a touch device. In order to take effect, chart.zoomType and chart.pinchType must be disabled.

summary.p: The HTML of the tooltip header line. Variables are enclosed by curly brackets. Available variablesare point.key, series.name, series.color and other members from the point and series objects. The point.key variable contains the category name, x value or datetime string depending on the type of axis. For datetime axes, the point.key date format can be set using tooltip.xDateFormat.
Defaults to {point.key}

The HTML of the point's line in the tooltip. Variables are enclosed by curly brackets. Available variables are point.x, point.y, point.change, series.name and series.color and other properties on the same form. Furthermore, point.y can be extended by the tooltip.valuePrefix and tooltip.valueSuffix variables. This can also be overridden for each series, which makes it a good hook for displaying units.

summary.p: Enable or disable the initial animation when a series is displayed. The animation can also be set as a configuration object. Please note that this option only applies to the initial animation of the series itself. For other animations, see chart.animation and the animation parameter under the API methods.The following properties are supported:

dl.dd: The duration of the animation in milliseconds.

When using jQuery as the general framework, the easing can be set to linear orswing. More easing functions are available with the use of jQuery plug-ins, most notablythe jQuery UI suite. See the jQuery docs. When using MooTools as the general framework, use the property name transition instead of easing.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.CandleStickSeries.CropThreshold
member.summary: When the series contains less points than the crop threshold, all points are drawn, event if the points fall outside the visible plot area at the current zoom. The advantage of drawing all points (including markers and columns), is that animation is performed on updates. On the other hand, when the series contains more points than the crop threshold, the series data is cropped to only contain points that fall within the plot area. The advantage of cropping away invisible points is to increase performance on large series. .

summary.p: Datetime formats for the header of the tooltip in a stock chart. The format can vary within a chart depending on the currently selected time range and the current data grouping.
The default formats are:

For each of these array definitions, the first item is the format used when the active time span is one unit. For instance, if the current data applies to one week, the first item of the week array is used. The second and third items are used when the active time span is more than two units. For instance, if the current data applies to two weeks, the second and third item of the week array are used, and applied to the start and end date of the time span.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.CandleStickSeriesDataGrouping.Forced
member.summary: When data grouping is forced, it runs no matter how small the intervals are. This can be handy for example when the sum should be calculated for values appearing at random times within each hour. Defaults to false.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.CandleStickSeriesDataGrouping.GroupPixelWidth
member.summary: The approximate pixel width of each group. If for example a series with 30 points is displayed over a 600 pixel wide plot area, no grouping is performed. If however the series contains so many points that the spacing is less than the groupPixelWidth, Highcharts will try to group it into appropriate groups so that each is more or less two pixels wide. summary.p: The HTML of the tooltip header line. Variables are enclosed by curly brackets. Available variablesare point.key, series.name, series.color and other members from the point and series objects. The point.key variable contains the category name, x value or datetime string depending on the type of axis. For datetime axes, the point.key date format can be set using tooltip.xDateFormat.
Defaults to {point.key}

The HTML of the point's line in the tooltip. Variables are enclosed by curly brackets. Available variables are point.x, point.y, point.change, series.name and series.color and other properties on the same form. Furthermore, point.y can be extended by the tooltip.valuePrefix and tooltip.valueSuffix variables. This can also be overridden for each series, which makes it a good hook for displaying units.

summary.p: Set the overall animation for all chart updating. Animation can be disabled throughout the chart by setting it to false here. It can be overridden for each individual API method as a function parameter. The only animation not affected by this option is the initial series animation, see plotOptions.series => animation.

The animation can either be set as a boolean or a configuration object. If true, it will use the 'swing' jQuery easing and a duration of 500 ms. If used as a configuration object, the following properties are supported:

dl.dd: The duration of the animation in milliseconds.

When using jQuery as the general framework, the easing can be set to linear or swing. More easing functions are available with the use of jQuery plug-ins, most notably the jQuery UI suite. See the jQuery docs. When using MooTools as the general framework, use the property name transition instead of easing.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.Chart.Width

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.Chart.ZoomType

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ChartEvents.AddSeries
member.summary: Fires when a series is added to the chart after load time, using the addSeries method. One parameter, event, is passed to the function. This contains common event information based on jQuery or MooTools depending on which library is used as the base for Highcharts. Through event.options you can access the series options that was passed to the addSeries method. Returning false prevents the series from being added.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ChartEvents.AfterPrint
member.summary: Fires after a chart is printed through the context menu item or the Chart.print method. Requires the exporting module.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ChartEvents.BeforePrint
member.summary: Fires before a chart is printed through the context menu item or the Chart.print method. Requires the exporting module.

summary.p: Fires when clicking on the plot background. One parameter, event, is passed to the function. This contains common event information based on jQuery or MooTools depending on which library is used as the base for Highcharts.

Information on the clicked spot can be found through event.xAxis and event.yAxis, which are arrays containing the axes of each dimension and each axis' value at the clicked spot. The primary axes are event.xAxis[0] and event.yAxis[0]. Remember the unit of a datetime axis is milliseconds since 1970-01-01 00:00:00.

Fires when the chart is finished loading. One parameter, event, is passed to the function. This contains common event information based on jQuery or MooTools depending on which library is used as the base for Highcharts.
From version 2.0.4, there is also a second parameter to Highcharts.Chart where a callback function can be passed to be executed on chart.load.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ChartEvents.Redraw
member.summary: Fires when the chart is redrawn, either after a call to chart.redraw() or after an axis, series or point is modified with the redraw option set to true. One parameter, event, is passed to the function. This contains common event information based on jQuery or MooTools depending on which library is used as the base for Highcharts.

summary.p: Fires when an area of the chart has been selected. Selection is enabled by setting the chart's zoomType. One parameter, event, is passed to the function. This contains common event information based on jQuery or MooTools depending on which library is used as the base for Highcharts. The default action for the selection event is to zoom the chart to the selected area. It can be prevented by calling event.preventDefault().

Information on the selected area can be found through event.xAxis and event.yAxis, which are arrays containing the axes of each dimension and each axis' min and max values. The primary axes are event.xAxis[0] and event.yAxis[0]. Remember the unit of a datetime axis is milliseconds since 1970-01-01 00:00:00.
summary.pre: selection: function(event) {// log the min and max of the primary, datetime x-axisconsole.log(Highcharts.dateFormat('%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S', event.xAxis[0].min),Highcharts.dateFormat('%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S', event.xAxis[0].max));// log the min and max of the y axisconsole.log(event.yAxis[0].min, event.yAxis[0].max);}

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ColumnrangeSeries.AllowPointSelect
member.summary: Allow this series' points to be selected by clicking on the markers or bars.

summary.p: Enable or disable the initial animation when a series is displayed. The animation can also be set as a configuration object. Please note that this option only applies to the initial animation of the series itself. For other animations, see chart.animation and the animation parameter under the API methods.The following properties are supported:

dl.dd: The duration of the animation in milliseconds.

When using jQuery as the general framework, the easing can be set to linear orswing. More easing functions are available with the use of jQuery plug-ins, most notablythe jQuery UI suite. See the jQuery docs. When using MooTools as the general framework, use the property name transition instead of easing.

summary.p: Due to poor performance, animation is disabled in old IE browsers for column charts and polar charts.

member.summary: The main color of the series. In line type series it applies to the line and the point markers unless otherwise specified. In bar type series it applies to the bars unless a color is specified per point. The default value is pulled from the options.colors array.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ColumnrangeSeries.ColorByPoint
member.summary: When using automatic point colors pulled from the options.colors collection, this option determines whether the chart should receive one color per series or one color per point.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ColumnrangeSeries.Colors
member.summary: A series specific or series type specific color set to apply instead of the global colors when colorByPoint is true.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ColumnrangeSeries.Compare
member.summary: Compare the values of the series against the first value in the visible range. The y axis will show percentage or absolute change depending on whether compare is set to "percent" or "value". When this is applied to multiple series, it allows comparing the development of the series against each other.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ColumnrangeSeries.CropThreshold
member.summary: When the series contains less points than the crop threshold, all points are drawn, event if the points fall outside the visible plot area at the current zoom. The advantage of drawing all points (including markers and columns), is that animation is performed on updates. On the other hand, when the series contains more points than the crop threshold, the series data is cropped to only contain points that fall within the plot area. The advantage of cropping away invisible points is to increase performance on large series. .

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ColumnrangeSeries.Cursor
member.summary: You can set the cursor to "pointer" if you have click events attached to the series, to signal to the user that the points and lines can be clicked.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ColumnrangeSeries.DataLabels
member.summary: Extended data labels for range series types. Range series data labels have no x and y options. Instead, they have xLow, xHigh, yLow and yHigh options to allow the higher and lower data label sets individually.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ColumnrangeSeries.EnableMouseTracking
member.summary: Enable or disable the mouse tracking for a specific series. This includes point tooltips and click events on graphs and points. When using shared tooltips (default in stock charts), mouse tracking is not required. For large datasets it improves performance.

member.summary: The minimal height for a column or width for a bar. By default, 0 values are not shown. To visualize a 0 (or close to zero) point, set the minimal point length to a pixel value like 3. In stacked column charts, minPointLength might not be respected for tightly packed values.

summary.p: If no x values are given for the points in a series, pointInterval defines the interval of the x values in milliseconds. For example, if a series contains one value each day, set pointInterval to 24 * 3600 * 1000.
Since Highstock 2.1, it can be combined with pointIntervalUnit to draw irregular intervals.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ColumnrangeSeries.PointIntervalUnit
member.summary: On datetime series, this allows for setting the pointInterval to the two irregular time units, month and year. Combine it with pointInterval to draw quarters, 6 months, 10 years etc.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ColumnrangeSeries.PointRange
member.summary: The width of each point on the x axis. For example in a column chart with one value each day, the pointRange would be 1 day (= 24 * 3600 * 1000 milliseconds). This is normally computed automatically, but this option can be used to override the automatic value. In a series on a categorized axis the pointRange is 1 by default.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ColumnrangeSeries.PointStart
member.summary: If no x values are given for the points in a series, pointStart defines on what value to start. On a datetime X axis, the number will be given as milliseconds since 1970-01-01, for example Date.UTC(2011, 0, 1).

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ColumnrangeSeries.PointWidth

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ColumnrangeSeries.StickyTracking
member.summary: Sticky tracking of mouse events. When true, the mouseOut event on a series isn't triggered until the mouse moves over another series, or out of the plot area. When false, the mouseOut event on a series is triggered when the mouse leaves the area around the series' graph or markers. This also implies the tooltip when not shared. When stickyTracking is false, the tooltip will be hidden when moving the mouse between series. Defaults to true for line and area type series, but to false for columns, candlesticks etc.

member.summary: When a series contains a data array that is longer than this, only one dimensional arrays of numbers, or two dimensional arrays with x and y values are allowed. Also, only the first point is tested, and the rest are assumed to be the same format. This saves expensive data checking and indexing in long series. Set it to 0 disable.

summary.p: Datetime formats for the header of the tooltip in a stock chart. The format can vary within a chart depending on the currently selected time range and the current data grouping.
The default formats are:

For each of these array definitions, the first item is the format used when the active time span is one unit. For instance, if the current data applies to one week, the first item of the week array is used. The second and third items are used when the active time span is more than two units. For instance, if the current data applies to two weeks, the second and third item of the week array are used, and applied to the start and end date of the time span.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ColumnrangeSeriesDataGrouping.Enabled
member.summary: Enable or disable data grouping. Defaults to true.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ColumnrangeSeriesDataGrouping.Forced
member.summary: When data grouping is forced, it runs no matter how small the intervals are. This can be handy for example when the sum should be calculated for values appearing at random times within each hour. Defaults to false.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ColumnrangeSeriesDataGrouping.GroupPixelWidth
member.summary: The approximate pixel width of each group. If for example a series with 30 points is displayed over a 600 pixel wide plot area, no grouping is performed. If however the series contains so many points that the spacing is less than the groupPixelWidth, Highcharts will try to group it into appropriate groups so that each is more or less two pixels wide. Defaults to 10.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ColumnrangeSeriesDataGrouping.Smoothed
member.summary: Normally, a group is indexed by the start of that group, so for example when 30 daily values are grouped into one month, that month's x value will be the 1st of the month. This apparently shifts the data to the left. When the smoothed option is true, this is compensated for. The data is shifted to the middle of the group, and min and max values are preserved. Internally, this is used in the Navigator series. Defaults to false.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ColumnrangeSeriesDataLabels.Align

For points with an extent, like columns, the alignments also dictates how to align it inside the box, as given with the inside option. Can be one of "left", "center" or "right".

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ColumnrangeSeriesDataLabels.Formatter
member.summary:
Callback JavaScript function to format the data label. Note that if a format is defined, the format takes precedence and the formatter is ignored. Available data are:
this.percentage Stacked series and pies only. The point's percentage of the total.
this.point The point object. The point name, if defined, is available through this.point.name.
this.series: The series object. The series name is available through this.series.name.
this.total Stacked series only. The total value at this point's x value.
this.x: The x value.
this.y: The y value.

member.summary: How to handle data labels that flow outside the plot area. The default is justify, which aligns them inside the plot area. For columns and bars, this means it will be moved inside the bar. To display data labels outside the plot area, set crop to false and overflow to "none".

summary.p: The HTML of the tooltip header line. Variables are enclosed by curly brackets. Available variablesare point.key, series.name, series.color and other members from the point and series objects. The point.key variable contains the category name, x value or datetime string depending on the type of axis. For datetime axes, the point.key date format can be set using tooltip.xDateFormat.
Defaults to {point.key}

The HTML of the point's line in the tooltip. Variables are enclosed by curly brackets. Available variables are point.x, point.y, point.change, series.name and series.color and other properties on the same form. Furthermore, point.y can be extended by the tooltip.valuePrefix and tooltip.valueSuffix variables. This can also be overridden for each series, which makes it a good hook for displaying units.

member.summary: Compare the values of the series against the first value in the visible range. The y axis will show percentage or absolute change depending on whether compare is set to "percent" or "value". When this is applied to multiple series, it allows comparing the development of the series against each other.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ColumnSeries.CropThreshold
member.summary: When the series contains less points than the crop threshold, all points are drawn, event if the points fall outside the visible plot area at the current zoom. The advantage of drawing all points (including markers and columns), is that animation is performed on updates. On the other hand, when the series contains more points than the crop threshold, the series data is cropped to only contain points that fall within the plot area. The advantage of cropping away invisible points is to increase performance on large series. .

summary.p: Datetime formats for the header of the tooltip in a stock chart. The format can vary within a chart depending on the currently selected time range and the current data grouping.
The default formats are:

For each of these array definitions, the first item is the format used when the active time span is one unit. For instance, if the current data applies to one week, the first item of the week array is used. The second and third items are used when the active time span is more than two units. For instance, if the current data applies to two weeks, the second and third item of the week array are used, and applied to the start and end date of the time span.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ColumnSeriesDataGrouping.Enabled
member.summary: Enable or disable data grouping. Defaults to true.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ColumnSeriesDataGrouping.Forced
member.summary: When data grouping is forced, it runs no matter how small the intervals are. This can be handy for example when the sum should be calculated for values appearing at random times within each hour. Defaults to false.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ColumnSeriesDataGrouping.GroupPixelWidth
member.summary: The approximate pixel width of each group. If for example a series with 30 points is displayed over a 600 pixel wide plot area, no grouping is performed. If however the series contains so many points that the spacing is less than the groupPixelWidth, Highcharts will try to group it into appropriate groups so that each is more or less two pixels wide. Defaults to 10.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ColumnSeriesDataGrouping.Smoothed
member.summary: Normally, a group is indexed by the start of that group, so for example when 30 daily values are grouped into one month, that month's x value will be the 1st of the month. This apparently shifts the data to the left. When the smoothed option is true, this is compensated for. The data is shifted to the middle of the group, and min and max values are preserved. Internally, this is used in the Navigator series. Defaults to false.

member.name: M:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ColumnSeriesDataGrouping.ToHashtable
member.summary: An array determining what time intervals the data is allowed to be grouped to. Each array item is an array where the first value is the time unit and the second value another array of allowed multiples. summary.p: The HTML of the tooltip header line. Variables are enclosed by curly brackets. Available variablesare point.key, series.name, series.color and other members from the point and series objects. The point.key variable contains the category name, x value or datetime string depending on the type of axis. For datetime axes, the point.key date format can be set using tooltip.xDateFormat.
Defaults to {point.key}

The HTML of the point's line in the tooltip. Variables are enclosed by curly brackets. Available variables are point.x, point.y, point.change, series.name and series.color and other properties on the same form. Furthermore, point.y can be extended by the tooltip.valuePrefix and tooltip.valueSuffix variables. This can also be overridden for each series, which makes it a good hook for displaying units.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.FlagsSeries.CropThreshold
member.summary: When the series contains less points than the crop threshold, all points are drawn, event if the points fall outside the visible plot area at the current zoom. The advantage of drawing all points (including markers and columns), is that animation is performed on updates. On the other hand, when the series contains more points than the crop threshold, the series data is cropped to only contain points that fall within the plot area. The advantage of cropping away invisible points is to increase performance on large series. .

Custom callbacks for symbol path generation can also be added to Highcharts.SVGRenderer.prototype.symbols. The callback is then used by its method name, as shown in the demo.

summary.p: Whether the tooltip should follow the mouse as it moves across columns, pie slices and other point types with an extent. By default it behaves this way for scatter, bubble and pie series by override in the plotOptions for those series types.
For touch moves to behave the same way, followTouchMove must be true also.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.FlagsSeriesTooltip.FollowTouchMove
member.summary: Whether the tooltip should follow the finger as it moves on a touch device. In order to take effect, chart.zoomType and chart.pinchType must be disabled.

summary.p: The HTML of the tooltip header line. Variables are enclosed by curly brackets. Available variablesare point.key, series.name, series.color and other members from the point and series objects. The point.key variable contains the category name, x value or datetime string depending on the type of axis. For datetime axes, the point.key date format can be set using tooltip.xDateFormat.
Defaults to {point.key}

The HTML of the point's line in the tooltip. Variables are enclosed by curly brackets. Available variables are point.x, point.y, point.change, series.name and series.color and other properties on the same form. Furthermore, point.y can be extended by the tooltip.valuePrefix and tooltip.valueSuffix variables. This can also be overridden for each series, which makes it a good hook for displaying units.

summary.p: The plotOptions is a wrapper object for config objects for each series type.The config objects for each series can also be overridden for each series item as given in the series array.

Configuration options for the series are given in three levels. Optionsfor all series in a chart are given in the plotOptions.series object. Then options for all seriesof a specific type are given in the plotOptions of that type, for example plotOptions.line.Next, options for one single series are given in the series array.

summary.p: Enable or disable the initial animation when a series is displayed. The animation can also be set as a configuration object. Please note that this option only applies to the initial animation of the series itself. For other animations, see chart.animation and the animation parameter under the API methods.The following properties are supported:

dl.dd: The duration of the animation in milliseconds.

When using jQuery as the general framework, the easing can be set to linear orswing. More easing functions are available with the use of jQuery plug-ins, most notablythe jQuery UI suite. See the jQuery docs. When using MooTools as the general framework, use the property name transition instead of easing.

summary.p: Due to poor performance, animation is disabled in old IE browsers for column charts and polar charts.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.LineSeries.Color
member.summary: The main color of the series. In line type series it applies to the line and the point markers unless otherwise specified. In bar type series it applies to the bars unless a color is specified per point. The default value is pulled from the options.colors array.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.LineSeries.Compare
member.summary: Compare the values of the series against the first value in the visible range. The y axis will show percentage or absolute change depending on whether compare is set to "percent" or "value". When this is applied to multiple series, it allows comparing the development of the series against each other.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.LineSeries.ConnectNulls
member.summary: Whether to draw a line between points on either side of a null point, or render a gap between them.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.LineSeries.CropThreshold
member.summary: When the series contains less points than the crop threshold, all points are drawn, event if the points fall outside the visible plot area at the current zoom. The advantage of drawing all points (including markers and columns), is that animation is performed on updates. On the other hand, when the series contains more points than the crop threshold, the series data is cropped to only contain points that fall within the plot area. The advantage of cropping away invisible points is to increase performance on large series. .

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.LineSeries.Cursor

A name for the dash style to use for the graph. Applies only to series type having a graph, like line, spline, area and scatter in case it has a lineWidth. The value for the dashStyle include:

Dot

LongDash

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.LineSeries.EnableMouseTracking
member.summary: Enable or disable the mouse tracking for a specific series. This includes point tooltips and click events on graphs and points. When using shared tooltips (default in stock charts), mouse tracking is not required. For large datasets it improves performance.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.LineSeries.GapSize
member.summary:
Defines when to display a gap in the graph. A gap size of 5 means that if the distance between two points is greater than five times that of the two closest points, the graph will be broken.
In practice, this option is most often used to visualize gaps in time series. In a stock chart, intraday data is available for daytime hours, while gaps will appear in nights and weekends..

Since Highstock 2.1, it can be combined with pointIntervalUnit to draw irregular intervals.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.LineSeries.PointIntervalUnit
member.summary: On datetime series, this allows for setting the pointInterval to the two irregular time units, month and year. Combine it with pointInterval to draw quarters, 6 months, 10 years etc.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.LineSeries.StickyTracking
member.summary: Sticky tracking of mouse events. When true, the mouseOut event on a series isn't triggered until the mouse moves over another series, or out of the plot area. When false, the mouseOut event on a series is triggered when the mouse leaves the area around the series' graph or markers. This also implies the tooltip when not shared. When stickyTracking is false, the tooltip will be hidden when moving the mouse between series. Defaults to true for line and area type series, but to false for columns, candlesticks etc.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.LineSeries.TurboThreshold
member.summary: When a series contains a data array that is longer than this, only one dimensional arrays of numbers, or two dimensional arrays with x and y values are allowed. Also, only the first point is tested, and the rest are assumed to be the same format. This saves expensive data checking and indexing in long series. Set it to 0 disable.

summary.p: Datetime formats for the header of the tooltip in a stock chart. The format can vary within a chart depending on the currently selected time range and the current data grouping.
The default formats are:

For each of these array definitions, the first item is the format used when the active time span is one unit. For instance, if the current data applies to one week, the first item of the week array is used. The second and third items are used when the active time span is more than two units. For instance, if the current data applies to two weeks, the second and third item of the week array are used, and applied to the start and end date of the time span.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.LineSeriesDataGrouping.Enabled
member.summary: Enable or disable data grouping. Defaults to true.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.LineSeriesDataGrouping.Forced
member.summary: When data grouping is forced, it runs no matter how small the intervals are. This can be handy for example when the sum should be calculated for values appearing at random times within each hour. Defaults to false.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.LineSeriesDataGrouping.GroupPixelWidth
member.summary: The approximate pixel width of each group. If for example a series with 30 points is displayed over a 600 pixel wide plot area, no grouping is performed. If however the series contains so many points that the spacing is less than the groupPixelWidth, Highcharts will try to group it into appropriate groups so that each is more or less two pixels wide. If multiple series with different group pixel widths are drawn on the same x axis, all series will take the greatest width. For example, line series have 2px default group width, while column series have 10px. If combined, both the line and the column will have 10px by default. Defaults to 2.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.LineSeriesDataGrouping.Smoothed
member.summary: Normally, a group is indexed by the start of that group, so for example when 30 daily values are grouped into one month, that month's x value will be the 1st of the month. This apparently shifts the data to the left. When the smoothed option is true, this is compensated for. The data is shifted to the middle of the group, and min and max values are preserved. Internally, this is used in the Navigator series. Defaults to false.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.LineSeriesDataLabels.Formatter
member.summary:
Callback JavaScript function to format the data label. Note that if a format is defined, the format takes precedence and the formatter is ignored. Available data are:
this.percentage Stacked series and pies only. The point's percentage of the total.
this.point The point object. The point name, if defined, is available through this.point.name.
this.series: The series object. The series name is available through this.series.name.
this.total Stacked series only. The total value at this point's x value.
this.x: The x value.
this.y: The y value.

member.summary: How to handle data labels that flow outside the plot area. The default is justify, which aligns them inside the plot area. For columns and bars, this means it will be moved inside the bar. To display data labels outside the plot area, set crop to false and overflow to "none".

summary.p: The HTML of the tooltip header line. Variables are enclosed by curly brackets. Available variablesare point.key, series.name, series.color and other members from the point and series objects. The point.key variable contains the category name, x value or datetime string depending on the type of axis. For datetime axes, the point.key date format can be set using tooltip.xDateFormat.
Defaults to {point.key}

The HTML of the point's line in the tooltip. Variables are enclosed by curly brackets. Available variables are point.x, point.y, point.change, series.name and series.color and other properties on the same form. Furthermore, point.y can be extended by the tooltip.valuePrefix and tooltip.valueSuffix variables. This can also be overridden for each series, which makes it a good hook for displaying units.

summary.p: Enable or disable the initial animation when a series is displayed. The animation can also be set as a configuration object. Please note that this option only applies to the initial animation of the series itself. For other animations, see chart.animation and the animation parameter under the API methods.The following properties are supported:

dl.dd: The duration of the animation in milliseconds.

When using jQuery as the general framework, the easing can be set to linear orswing. More easing functions are available with the use of jQuery plug-ins, most notablythe jQuery UI suite. See the jQuery docs. When using MooTools as the general framework, use the property name transition instead of easing.

summary.p: Due to poor performance, animation is disabled in old IE browsers for column charts and polar charts.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.OhlcSeries.Compare
member.summary: Compare the values of the series against the first value in the visible range. The y axis will show percentage or absolute change depending on whether compare is set to "percent" or "value". When this is applied to multiple series, it allows comparing the development of the series against each other.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.OhlcSeries.CropThreshold
member.summary: When the series contains less points than the crop threshold, all points are drawn, event if the points fall outside the visible plot area at the current zoom. The advantage of drawing all points (including markers and columns), is that animation is performed on updates. On the other hand, when the series contains more points than the crop threshold, the series data is cropped to only contain points that fall within the plot area. The advantage of cropping away invisible points is to increase performance on large series. .

summary.p: Datetime formats for the header of the tooltip in a stock chart. The format can vary within a chart depending on the currently selected time range and the current data grouping.
The default formats are:

For each of these array definitions, the first item is the format used when the active time span is one unit. For instance, if the current data applies to one week, the first item of the week array is used. The second and third items are used when the active time span is more than two units. For instance, if the current data applies to two weeks, the second and third item of the week array are used, and applied to the start and end date of the time span.

member.summary: Enable or disable data grouping. Defaults to true.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.OhlcSeriesDataGrouping.Forced
member.summary: When data grouping is forced, it runs no matter how small the intervals are. This can be handy for example when the sum should be calculated for values appearing at random times within each hour. Defaults to false.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.OhlcSeriesDataGrouping.GroupPixelWidth
member.summary: The approximate pixel width of each group. If for example a series with 30 points is displayed over a 600 pixel wide plot area, no grouping is performed. If however the series contains so many points that the spacing is less than the groupPixelWidth, Highcharts will try to group it into appropriate groups so that each is more or less two pixels wide. Defaults to 10.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.OhlcSeriesDataGrouping.Smoothed
member.summary: Normally, a group is indexed by the start of that group, so for example when 30 daily values are grouped into one month, that month's x value will be the 1st of the month. This apparently shifts the data to the left. When the smoothed option is true, this is compensated for. The data is shifted to the middle of the group, and min and max values are preserved. Internally, this is used in the Navigator series. Defaults to false.

member.summary: How many decimals to show for the point.change value when the series.compare option is set. This is overridable in each series' tooltip options object. The default is to preserve all decimals.

summary.p: Whether the tooltip should follow the mouse as it moves across columns, pie slices and other point types with an extent. By default it behaves this way for scatter, bubble and pie series by override in the plotOptions for those series types.
For touch moves to behave the same way, followTouchMove must be true also.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.OhlcSeriesTooltip.FollowTouchMove
member.summary: Whether the tooltip should follow the finger as it moves on a touch device. In order to take effect, chart.zoomType and chart.pinchType must be disabled.

summary.p: The HTML of the tooltip header line. Variables are enclosed by curly brackets. Available variablesare point.key, series.name, series.color and other members from the point and series objects. The point.key variable contains the category name, x value or datetime string depending on the type of axis. For datetime axes, the point.key date format can be set using tooltip.xDateFormat.
Defaults to {point.key}

The HTML of the point's line in the tooltip. Variables are enclosed by curly brackets. Available variables are point.x, point.y, point.change, series.name and series.color and other properties on the same form. Furthermore, point.y can be extended by the tooltip.valuePrefix and tooltip.valueSuffix variables. This can also be overridden for each series, which makes it a good hook for displaying units.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.OhlcSeriesTooltip.PointFormatter
member.summary: A callback function for formatting the HTML output for a single point in the tooltip. Like the pointFormat string, but with more flexibility.
