summary.p: Enable or disable the initial animation when a series is displayed. The animation can also be set as a configuration object. Please note that this option only applies to the initial animation of the series itself. For other animations, see chart.animation and the animation parameter under the API methods.The following properties are supported:

dl.dd: The duration of the animation in milliseconds.

When using jQuery as the general framework, the easing can be set to linear orswing. More easing functions are available with the use of jQuery plug-ins, most notablythe jQuery UI suite. See the jQuery docs. When using MooTools as the general framework, use the property name transition instead of easing.

summary.p: Due to poor performance, animation is disabled in old IE browsers for column charts and polar charts.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsPolygon.Color
member.summary: The main color of the series. In line type series it applies to the line and the point markers unless otherwise specified. In bar type series it applies to the bars unless a color is specified per point. The default value is pulled from the options.colors array.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsPolygon.Compare
member.summary: Compare the values of the series against the first value in the visible range. The y axis will show percentage or absolute change depending on whether compare is set to "percent" or "value". When this is applied to multiple series, it allows comparing the development of the series against each other.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsPolygon.CropThreshold
member.summary: When the series contains less points than the crop threshold, all points are drawn, event if the points fall outside the visible plot area at the current zoom. The advantage of drawing all points (including markers and columns), is that animation is performed on updates. On the other hand, when the series contains more points than the crop threshold, the series data is cropped to only contain points that fall within the plot area. The advantage of cropping away invisible points is to increase performance on large series. .

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsPolygon.Cursor
member.summary: You can set the cursor to "pointer" if you have click events attached to the series, to signal to the user that the points and lines can be clicked.

member.summary: The id of another series to link to. Additionally, the value can be ":previous" to link to the previous series. When two series are linked, only the first one appears in the legend. Toggling the visibility of this also toggles the linked series.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsPolygon.Point
member.summary: Properties for each single point

summary.p: If no x values are given for the points in a series, pointInterval defines the interval of the x values in milliseconds. For example, if a series contains one value each day, set pointInterval to 24 * 3600 * 1000.
Since Highstock 2.1, it can be combined with pointIntervalUnit to draw irregular intervals.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsPolygon.PointIntervalUnit
member.summary: On datetime series, this allows for setting the pointInterval to the two irregular time units, month and year. Combine it with pointInterval to draw quarters, 6 months, 10 years etc.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsPolygon.PointRange
member.summary: The width of each point on the x axis. For example in a column chart with one value each day, the pointRange would be 1 day (= 24 * 3600 * 1000 milliseconds). This is normally computed automatically, but this option can be used to override the automatic value.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsPolygon.PointStart
member.summary: If no x values are given for the points in a series, pointStart defines on what value to start. On a datetime X axis, the number will be given as milliseconds since 1970-01-01, for example Date.UTC(2011, 0, 1).

member.summary: Whether to select the series initially. If showCheckbox is true, the checkbox next to the series name in the legend will be checked for a selected series.

member.summary: Whether to apply a drop shadow to the graph line. Since 1.1.7 the shadow can be an object configuration containing color, offsetX, offsetY, opacity and width.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsPolygon.ShowCheckbox
member.summary: If true, a checkbox is displayed next to the legend item to allow selecting the series. The state of the checkbox is determined by the selected option.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsPolygon.ShowInLegend
member.summary: Whether to display this particular series or series type in the legend. The default value is true for standalone series, false for linked series.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsPolygon.Stacking
member.summary: Whether to stack the values of each series on top of each other. Possible values are null to disable, "normal" to stack by value or "percent".

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsPolygon.States
member.summary: A wrapper object for all the series options in specific states.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsPolygon.StickyTracking
member.summary: Sticky tracking of mouse events. When true, the mouseOut event on a series isn't triggered until the mouse moves over another series, or out of the plot area. When false, the mouseOut event on a series is triggered when the mouse leaves the area around the series' graph or markers. This also implies the tooltip. When stickyTracking is false and tooltip.shared is false, the tooltip will be hidden when moving the mouse between series.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsPolygon.TurboThreshold
member.summary: When a series contains a data array that is longer than this, only one dimensional arrays of numbers, or two dimensional arrays with x and y values are allowed. Also, only the first point is tested, and the rest are assumed to be the same format. This saves expensive data checking and indexing in long series. Set it to 0 disable.

summary.p: Datetime formats for the header of the tooltip in a stock chart. The format can vary within a chart depending on the currently selected time range and the current data grouping.
The default formats are:

For each of these array definitions, the first item is the format used when the active time span is one unit. For instance, if the current data applies to one week, the first item of the week array is used. The second and third items are used when the active time span is more than two units. For instance, if the current data applies to two weeks, the second and third item of the week array are used, and applied to the start and end date of the time span.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsPolygonDataGrouping.Enabled
member.summary: Enable or disable data grouping. Defaults to true.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsPolygonDataGrouping.Forced
member.summary: When data grouping is forced, it runs no matter how small the intervals are. This can be handy for example when the sum should be calculated for values appearing at random times within each hour. Defaults to false.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsPolygonDataGrouping.GroupPixelWidth
member.summary: The approximate pixel width of each group. If for example a series with 30 points is displayed over a 600 pixel wide plot area, no grouping is performed. If however the series contains so many points that the spacing is less than the groupPixelWidth, Highcharts will try to group it into appropriate groups so that each is more or less two pixels wide. If multiple series with different group pixel widths are drawn on the same x axis, all series will take the greatest width. For example, line series have 2px default group width, while column series have 10px. If combined, both the line and the column will have 10px by default. Defaults to 2.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsPolygonDataGrouping.Smoothed
member.summary: Normally, a group is indexed by the start of that group, so for example when 30 daily values are grouped into one month, that month's x value will be the 1st of the month. This apparently shifts the data to the left. When the smoothed option is true, this is compensated for. The data is shifted to the middle of the group, and min and max values are preserved. Internally, this is used in the Navigator series. Defaults to false.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsPolygonDataLabels.Align

member.summary:
Callback JavaScript function to format the data label. Note that if a format is defined, the format takes precedence and the formatter is ignored. Available data are:
this.percentage Stacked series and pies only. The point's percentage of the total.
this.point The point object. The point name, if defined, is available through this.point.name.

Fires when a point is clicked. One parameter, event, is passed to the function. This contains common event information based on jQuery or MooTools depending on which library is used as the base for Highcharts.
If the series.allowPointSelect option is true, the default action for the point's click event is to toggle the point's select state. Returning false cancels this action.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsPolygonStatesHover.Enabled
member.summary: Enable separate styles for the hovered series to visualize that the user hovers either the series itself or the legend. Enabling it has a performance penalty as it requires that a second layer be drawn as a double buffer. This means twice as much graphics to draw for each plot, which can make a great difference for charts with a high number of series or points..

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsPolygonStatesHover.Halo
member.summary: Options for the halo appearing around the hovered point in line-type series as well as outside the hovered slice in pie charts. By default the halo is filled by the current point or series color with an opacity of 0.25. The halo can be disabled by setting the halo option to false.

summary.p: A predefined shape or symbol for the marker. When null, the symbol is pulled from options.symbols. Other possible values are "circle", "square", "diamond", "triangle" and "triangle-down".

summary.p: Enable or disable the initial animation when a series is displayed. The animation can also be set as a configuration object. Please note that this option only applies to the initial animation of the series itself. For other animations, see chart.animation and the animation parameter under the API methods.The following properties are supported:

dl.dd: The duration of the animation in milliseconds.

When using jQuery as the general framework, the easing can be set to linear orswing. More easing functions are available with the use of jQuery plug-ins, most notablythe jQuery UI suite. See the jQuery docs. When using MooTools as the general framework, use the property name transition instead of easing.

summary.p: Due to poor performance, animation is disabled in old IE browsers for column charts and polar charts.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsScatter.Color
member.summary: The main color of the series. In line type series it applies to the line and the point markers unless otherwise specified. In bar type series it applies to the bars unless a color is specified per point. The default value is pulled from the options.colors array.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsScatter.Compare
member.summary: Compare the values of the series against the first value in the visible range. The y axis will show percentage or absolute change depending on whether compare is set to "percent" or "value". When this is applied to multiple series, it allows comparing the development of the series against each other.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsScatter.CropThreshold
member.summary: When the series contains less points than the crop threshold, all points are drawn, event if the points fall outside the visible plot area at the current zoom. The advantage of drawing all points (including markers and columns), is that animation is performed on updates. On the other hand, when the series contains more points than the crop threshold, the series data is cropped to only contain points that fall within the plot area. The advantage of cropping away invisible points is to increase performance on large series. .

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsScatter.Cursor
member.summary: You can set the cursor to "pointer" if you have click events attached to the series, to signal to the user that the points and lines can be clicked.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsScatter.Point
member.summary: Properties for each single point

summary.p: If no x values are given for the points in a series, pointInterval defines the interval of the x values in milliseconds. For example, if a series contains one value each day, set pointInterval to 24 * 3600 * 1000.
Since Highstock 2.1, it can be combined with pointIntervalUnit to draw irregular intervals.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsScatter.PointIntervalUnit
member.summary: On datetime series, this allows for setting the pointInterval to the two irregular time units, month and year. Combine it with pointInterval to draw quarters, 6 months, 10 years etc.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsScatter.PointRange
member.summary: The width of each point on the x axis. For example in a column chart with one value each day, the pointRange would be 1 day (= 24 * 3600 * 1000 milliseconds). This is normally computed automatically, but this option can be used to override the automatic value.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsScatter.PointStart
member.summary: If no x values are given for the points in a series, pointStart defines on what value to start. On a datetime X axis, the number will be given as milliseconds since 1970-01-01, for example Date.UTC(2011, 0, 1).

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsScatter.ShowCheckbox
member.summary: If true, a checkbox is displayed next to the legend item to allow selecting the series. The state of the checkbox is determined by the selected option.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsScatter.ShowInLegend
member.summary: Whether to display this particular series or series type in the legend. The default value is true for standalone series, false for linked series.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsScatter.Stacking
member.summary: Whether to stack the values of each series on top of each other. Possible values are null to disable, "normal" to stack by value or "percent".

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsScatter.States
member.summary: A wrapper object for all the series options in specific states.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsScatter.StickyTracking
member.summary: Sticky tracking of mouse events. When true, the mouseOut event on a series isn't triggered until the mouse moves over another series, or out of the plot area. When false, the mouseOut event on a series is triggered when the mouse leaves the area around the series' graph or markers. This also implies the tooltip. When stickyTracking is false and tooltip.shared is false, the tooltip will be hidden when moving the mouse between series.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsScatter.TurboThreshold
member.summary: When a series contains a data array that is longer than this, only one dimensional arrays of numbers, or two dimensional arrays with x and y values are allowed. Also, only the first point is tested, and the rest are assumed to be the same format. This saves expensive data checking and indexing in long series. Set it to 0 disable.

summary.p: Datetime formats for the header of the tooltip in a stock chart. The format can vary within a chart depending on the currently selected time range and the current data grouping.
The default formats are:

For each of these array definitions, the first item is the format used when the active time span is one unit. For instance, if the current data applies to one week, the first item of the week array is used. The second and third items are used when the active time span is more than two units. For instance, if the current data applies to two weeks, the second and third item of the week array are used, and applied to the start and end date of the time span.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsScatterDataGrouping.Enabled
member.summary: Enable or disable data grouping. Defaults to true.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsScatterDataGrouping.Forced
member.summary: When data grouping is forced, it runs no matter how small the intervals are. This can be handy for example when the sum should be calculated for values appearing at random times within each hour. Defaults to false.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsScatterDataGrouping.GroupPixelWidth
member.summary: The approximate pixel width of each group. If for example a series with 30 points is displayed over a 600 pixel wide plot area, no grouping is performed. If however the series contains so many points that the spacing is less than the groupPixelWidth, Highcharts will try to group it into appropriate groups so that each is more or less two pixels wide. If multiple series with different group pixel widths are drawn on the same x axis, all series will take the greatest width. For example, line series have 2px default group width, while column series have 10px. If combined, both the line and the column will have 10px by default. Defaults to 2.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsScatterDataGrouping.Smoothed
member.summary: Normally, a group is indexed by the start of that group, so for example when 30 daily values are grouped into one month, that month's x value will be the 1st of the month. This apparently shifts the data to the left. When the smoothed option is true, this is compensated for. The data is shifted to the middle of the group, and min and max values are preserved. Internally, this is used in the Navigator series. Defaults to false.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsScatterDataLabels.Formatter
member.summary:
Callback JavaScript function to format the data label. Note that if a format is defined, the format takes precedence and the formatter is ignored. Available data are:
this.percentage Stacked series and pies only. The point's percentage of the total.
this.point The point object. The point name, if defined, is available through this.point.name.
this.series: The series object. The series name is available through this.series.name.
this.total Stacked series only. The total value at this point's x value.
this.x: The x value.
this.y: The y value.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsScatterStatesHover.Enabled
member.summary: Enable separate styles for the hovered series to visualize that the user hovers either the series itself or the legend. Enabling it has a performance penalty as it requires that a second layer be drawn as a double buffer. This means twice as much graphics to draw for each plot, which can make a great difference for charts with a high number of series or points..

summary.p: Enable or disable the initial animation when a series is displayed. The animation can also be set as a configuration object. Please note that this option only applies to the initial animation of the series itself. For other animations, see chart.animation and the animation parameter under the API methods.The following properties are supported:

dl.dd: The duration of the animation in milliseconds.

When using jQuery as the general framework, the easing can be set to linear orswing. More easing functions are available with the use of jQuery plug-ins, most notablythe jQuery UI suite. See the jQuery docs. When using MooTools as the general framework, use the property name transition instead of easing.

summary.p: Due to poor performance, animation is disabled in old IE browsers for column charts and polar charts.

member.summary: The main color of the series. In line type series it applies to the line and the point markers unless otherwise specified. In bar type series it applies to the bars unless a color is specified per point. The default value is pulled from the options.colors array.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsSeries.Compare
member.summary: Compare the values of the series against the first value in the visible range. The y axis will show percentage or absolute change depending on whether compare is set to "percent" or "value". When this is applied to multiple series, it allows comparing the development of the series against each other.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsSeries.ConnectNulls
member.summary: Whether to draw a line between points on either side of a null point, or render a gap between them.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsSeries.CropThreshold
member.summary: When the series contains less points than the crop threshold, all points are drawn, event if the points fall outside the visible plot area at the current zoom. The advantage of drawing all points (including markers and columns), is that animation is performed on updates. On the other hand, when the series contains more points than the crop threshold, the series data is cropped to only contain points that fall within the plot area. The advantage of cropping away invisible points is to increase performance on large series. .

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsSeries.Cursor

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsSeries.EnableMouseTracking
member.summary: Enable or disable the mouse tracking for a specific series. This includes point tooltips and click events on graphs and points. When using shared tooltips (default in stock charts), mouse tracking is not required. For large datasets it improves performance.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsSeries.GapSize
member.summary:
Defines when to display a gap in the graph. A gap size of 5 means that if the distance between two points is greater than five times that of the two closest points, the graph will be broken.
In practice, this option is most often used to visualize gaps in time series. In a stock chart, intraday data is available for daytime hours, while gaps will appear in nights and weekends..

summary.p: If no x values are given for the points in a series, pointInterval defines the interval of the x values in milliseconds. For example, if a series contains one value each day, set pointInterval to 24 * 3600 * 1000.
Since Highstock 2.1, it can be combined with pointIntervalUnit to draw irregular intervals.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsSeries.PointIntervalUnit
member.summary: On datetime series, this allows for setting the pointInterval to the two irregular time units, month and year. Combine it with pointInterval to draw quarters, 6 months, 10 years etc.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsSeries.PointRange
member.summary: The width of each point on the x axis. For example in a column chart with one value each day, the pointRange would be 1 day (= 24 * 3600 * 1000 milliseconds). This is normally computed automatically, but this option can be used to override the automatic value.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsSeries.PointStart
member.summary: If no x values are given for the points in a series, pointStart defines on what value to start. On a datetime X axis, the number will be given as milliseconds since 1970-01-01, for example Date.UTC(2011, 0, 1).

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsSeries.StickyTracking
member.summary: Sticky tracking of mouse events. When true, the mouseOut event on a series isn't triggered until the mouse moves over another series, or out of the plot area. When false, the mouseOut event on a series is triggered when the mouse leaves the area around the series' graph or markers. This also implies the tooltip when not shared. When stickyTracking is false, the tooltip will be hidden when moving the mouse between series. Defaults to true for line and area type series, but to false for columns, candlesticks etc.

member.summary: A configuration object for the tooltip rendering of each single series. Properties are inherited from tooltip, but only the following properties can be defined on a series level.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsSeries.TurboThreshold
member.summary: When a series contains a data array that is longer than this, only one dimensional arrays of numbers, or two dimensional arrays with x and y values are allowed. Also, only the first point is tested, and the rest are assumed to be the same format. This saves expensive data checking and indexing in long series. Set it to 0 disable.

summary.p: Datetime formats for the header of the tooltip in a stock chart. The format can vary within a chart depending on the currently selected time range and the current data grouping.
The default formats are:

For each of these array definitions, the first item is the format used when the active time span is one unit. For instance, if the current data applies to one week, the first item of the week array is used. The second and third items are used when the active time span is more than two units. For instance, if the current data applies to two weeks, the second and third item of the week array are used, and applied to the start and end date of the time span.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsSeriesDataGrouping.Enabled
member.summary: Enable or disable data grouping. Defaults to true.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsSeriesDataGrouping.Forced
member.summary: When data grouping is forced, it runs no matter how small the intervals are. This can be handy for example when the sum should be calculated for values appearing at random times within each hour. Defaults to false.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsSeriesDataGrouping.GroupPixelWidth
member.summary: The approximate pixel width of each group. If for example a series with 30 points is displayed over a 600 pixel wide plot area, no grouping is performed. If however the series contains so many points that the spacing is less than the groupPixelWidth, Highcharts will try to group it into appropriate groups so that each is more or less two pixels wide. If multiple series with different group pixel widths are drawn on the same x axis, all series will take the greatest width. For example, line series have 2px default group width, while column series have 10px. If combined, both the line and the column will have 10px by default. Defaults to 2.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsSeriesDataGrouping.Smoothed
member.summary: Normally, a group is indexed by the start of that group, so for example when 30 daily values are grouped into one month, that month's x value will be the 1st of the month. This apparently shifts the data to the left. When the smoothed option is true, this is compensated for. The data is shifted to the middle of the group, and min and max values are preserved. Internally, this is used in the Navigator series. Defaults to false.

member.summary:
Callback JavaScript function to format the data label. Note that if a format is defined, the format takes precedence and the formatter is ignored. Available data are:
this.percentage Stacked series and pies only. The point's percentage of the total.

this.total Stacked series only. The total value at this point's x value.

summary.p: The HTML of the tooltip header line. Variables are enclosed by curly brackets. Available variablesare point.key, series.name, series.color and other members from the point and series objects. The point.key variable contains the category name, x value or datetime string depending on the type of axis. For datetime axes, the point.key date format can be set using tooltip.xDateFormat.
Defaults to {point.key}

The HTML of the point's line in the tooltip. Variables are enclosed by curly brackets. Available variables are point.x, point.y, point.change, series.name and series.color and other properties on the same form. Furthermore, point.y can be extended by the tooltip.valuePrefix and tooltip.valueSuffix variables. This can also be overridden for each series, which makes it a good hook for displaying units.

summary.p: Enable or disable the initial animation when a series is displayed. The animation can also be set as a configuration object. Please note that this option only applies to the initial animation of the series itself. For other animations, see chart.animation and the animation parameter under the API methods.The following properties are supported:

dl.dd: The duration of the animation in milliseconds.

When using jQuery as the general framework, the easing can be set to linear orswing. More easing functions are available with the use of jQuery plug-ins, most notablythe jQuery UI suite. See the jQuery docs. When using MooTools as the general framework, use the property name transition instead of easing.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsSpline.Compare
member.summary: Compare the values of the series against the first value in the visible range. The y axis will show percentage or absolute change depending on whether compare is set to "percent" or "value". When this is applied to multiple series, it allows comparing the development of the series against each other.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsSpline.ConnectNulls
member.summary: Whether to draw a line between points on either side of a null point, or render a gap between them.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsSpline.CropThreshold
member.summary: When the series contains less points than the crop threshold, all points are drawn, event if the points fall outside the visible plot area at the current zoom. The advantage of drawing all points (including markers and columns), is that animation is performed on updates. On the other hand, when the series contains more points than the crop threshold, the series data is cropped to only contain points that fall within the plot area. The advantage of cropping away invisible points is to increase performance on large series. .

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsSpline.Cursor

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsSpline.EnableMouseTracking
member.summary: Enable or disable the mouse tracking for a specific series. This includes point tooltips and click events on graphs and points. When using shared tooltips (default in stock charts), mouse tracking is not required. For large datasets it improves performance.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsSpline.GapSize
member.summary:
Defines when to display a gap in the graph. A gap size of 5 means that if the distance between two points is greater than five times that of the two closest points, the graph will be broken.
In practice, this option is most often used to visualize gaps in time series. In a stock chart, intraday data is available for daytime hours, while gaps will appear in nights and weekends..

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsSpline.PointIntervalUnit

member.summary: If no x values are given for the points in a series, pointStart defines on what value to start. On a datetime X axis, the number will be given as milliseconds since 1970-01-01, for example Date.UTC(2011, 0, 1).

member.summary: Sticky tracking of mouse events. When true, the mouseOut event on a series isn't triggered until the mouse moves over another series, or out of the plot area. When stickyTracking is false, the tooltip will be hidden when moving the mouse between series. Defaults to true for line and area type series, but to false for columns, candlesticks etc.

member.summary: When a series contains a data array that is longer than this, only one dimensional arrays of numbers, or two dimensional arrays with x and y values are allowed. Also, only the first point is tested, and the rest are assumed to be the same format. This saves expensive data checking and indexing in long series. Set it to 0 disable.

summary.p: Datetime formats for the header of the tooltip in a stock chart. The format can vary within a chart depending on the currently selected time range and the current data grouping.
The default formats are:

For each of these array definitions, the first item is the format used when the active time span is one unit. For instance, if the current data applies to one week, the first item of the week array is used. The second and third items are used when the active time span is more than two units. For instance, if the current data applies to two weeks, the second and third item of the week array are used, and applied to the start and end date of the time span.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsSplineDataGrouping.Enabled
member.summary: Enable or disable data grouping. Defaults to true.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsSplineDataGrouping.Forced
member.summary: When data grouping is forced, it runs no matter how small the intervals are. This can be handy for example when the sum should be calculated for values appearing at random times within each hour. Defaults to false.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsSplineDataGrouping.GroupPixelWidth
member.summary: The approximate pixel width of each group. If for example a series with 30 points is displayed over a 600 pixel wide plot area, no grouping is performed. If however the series contains so many points that the spacing is less than the groupPixelWidth, Highcharts will try to group it into appropriate groups so that each is more or less two pixels wide. If multiple series with different group pixel widths are drawn on the same x axis, all series will take the greatest width. For example, line series have 2px default group width, while column series have 10px. If combined, both the line and the column will have 10px by default. Defaults to 2.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsSplineDataGrouping.Smoothed
member.summary: Normally, a group is indexed by the start of that group, so for example when 30 daily values are grouped into one month, that month's x value will be the 1st of the month. This apparently shifts the data to the left. When the smoothed option is true, this is compensated for. The data is shifted to the middle of the group, and min and max values are preserved. Internally, this is used in the Navigator series. Defaults to false.

summary.p: A predefined shape or symbol for the marker. When null, the symbol is pulled from options.symbols. Other possible values are "circle", "square", "diamond", "triangle" and "triangle-down".

Custom callbacks for symbol path generation can also be added to Highcharts.SVGRenderer.prototype.symbols. The callback is then used by its method name, as shown in the demo.

summary.p: Whether the tooltip should follow the mouse as it moves across columns, pie slices and other point types with an extent. By default it behaves this way for scatter, bubble and pie series by override in the plotOptions for those series types.
For touch moves to behave the same way, followTouchMove must be true also.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PlotOptionsSplineTooltip.FollowTouchMove
member.summary: Whether the tooltip should follow the finger as it moves on a touch device. In order to take effect, chart.zoomType and chart.pinchType must be disabled.

summary.p: The HTML of the tooltip header line. Variables are enclosed by curly brackets. Available variablesare point.key, series.name, series.color and other members from the point and series objects. The point.key variable contains the category name, x value or datetime string depending on the type of axis. For datetime axes, the point.key date format can be set using tooltip.xDateFormat.
Defaults to {point.key}

The HTML of the point's line in the tooltip. Variables are enclosed by curly brackets. Available variables are point.x, point.y, point.change, series.name and series.color and other properties on the same form. Furthermore, point.y can be extended by the tooltip.valuePrefix and tooltip.valueSuffix variables. This can also be overridden for each series, which makes it a good hook for displaying units.

summary.p: Enable or disable the initial animation when a series is displayed. The animation can also be set as a configuration object. Please note that this option only applies to the initial animation of the series itself. For other animations, see chart.animation and the animation parameter under the API methods.The following properties are supported:

dl.dd: The duration of the animation in milliseconds.

When using jQuery as the general framework, the easing can be set to linear orswing. More easing functions are available with the use of jQuery plug-ins, most notablythe jQuery UI suite. See the jQuery docs. When using MooTools as the general framework, use the property name transition instead of easing.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PolygonSeries.Compare
member.summary: Compare the values of the series against the first value in the visible range. The y axis will show percentage or absolute change depending on whether compare is set to "percent" or "value". When this is applied to multiple series, it allows comparing the development of the series against each other.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PolygonSeries.CropThreshold
member.summary: When the series contains less points than the crop threshold, all points are drawn, event if the points fall outside the visible plot area at the current zoom. The advantage of drawing all points (including markers and columns), is that animation is performed on updates. On the other hand, when the series contains more points than the crop threshold, the series data is cropped to only contain points that fall within the plot area. The advantage of cropping away invisible points is to increase performance on large series. .

summary.p: Datetime formats for the header of the tooltip in a stock chart. The format can vary within a chart depending on the currently selected time range and the current data grouping.
The default formats are:

For each of these array definitions, the first item is the format used when the active time span is one unit. For instance, if the current data applies to one week, the first item of the week array is used. The second and third items are used when the active time span is more than two units. For instance, if the current data applies to two weeks, the second and third item of the week array are used, and applied to the start and end date of the time span.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PolygonSeriesDataGrouping.Enabled
member.summary: Enable or disable data grouping. Defaults to true.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PolygonSeriesDataGrouping.Forced
member.summary: When data grouping is forced, it runs no matter how small the intervals are. This can be handy for example when the sum should be calculated for values appearing at random times within each hour. Defaults to false.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PolygonSeriesDataGrouping.GroupPixelWidth
member.summary: The approximate pixel width of each group. If for example a series with 30 points is displayed over a 600 pixel wide plot area, no grouping is performed. If however the series contains so many points that the spacing is less than the groupPixelWidth, Highcharts will try to group it into appropriate groups so that each is more or less two pixels wide. If multiple series with different group pixel widths are drawn on the same x axis, all series will take the greatest width. For example, line series have 2px default group width, while column series have 10px. If combined, both the line and the column will have 10px by default. Defaults to 2.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PolygonSeriesDataGrouping.Smoothed
member.summary: Normally, a group is indexed by the start of that group, so for example when 30 daily values are grouped into one month, that month's x value will be the 1st of the month. This apparently shifts the data to the left. When the smoothed option is true, this is compensated for. The data is shifted to the middle of the group, and min and max values are preserved. Internally, this is used in the Navigator series. Defaults to false.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.PolygonSeriesDataLabels.Align
member.summary: The alignment of the data label compared to the point. If right, the right side of the label should be touching the point. For points with an extent, like columns, the alignments also dictates how to align it inside the box, as given with the inside option. Can be one of "left", "center" or "right".

member.summary:
Callback JavaScript function to format the data label. Note that if a format is defined, the format takes precedence and the formatter is ignored. Available data are:
this.percentage Stacked series and pies only. The point's percentage of the total.
this.point The point object. The point name, if defined, is available through this.point.name.
this.series: The series object. The series name is available through this.series.name.
this.total Stacked series only. The total value at this point's x value.
this.x: The x value.
this.y: The y value.

summary.p: Enable or disable the initial animation when a series is displayed. The animation can also be set as a configuration object. Please note that this option only applies to the initial animation of the series itself. For other animations, see chart.animation and the animation parameter under the API methods.The following properties are supported:

dl.dd: The duration of the animation in milliseconds.

When using jQuery as the general framework, the easing can be set to linear orswing. More easing functions are available with the use of jQuery plug-ins, most notablythe jQuery UI suite. See the jQuery docs. When using MooTools as the general framework, use the property name transition instead of easing.

summary.p: Due to poor performance, animation is disabled in old IE browsers for column charts and polar charts.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ScatterSeries.Color
member.summary: The main color of the series. In line type series it applies to the line and the point markers unless otherwise specified. In bar type series it applies to the bars unless a color is specified per point. The default value is pulled from the options.colors array.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ScatterSeries.Compare
member.summary: Compare the values of the series against the first value in the visible range. The y axis will show percentage or absolute change depending on whether compare is set to "percent" or "value". When this is applied to multiple series, it allows comparing the development of the series against each other.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ScatterSeries.CropThreshold
member.summary: When the series contains less points than the crop threshold, all points are drawn, event if the points fall outside the visible plot area at the current zoom. The advantage of drawing all points (including markers and columns), is that animation is performed on updates. On the other hand, when the series contains more points than the crop threshold, the series data is cropped to only contain points that fall within the plot area. The advantage of cropping away invisible points is to increase performance on large series. .

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ScatterSeries.Cursor

Solid

Dot

Since Highstock 2.1, it can be combined with pointIntervalUnit to draw irregular intervals.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ScatterSeries.PointIntervalUnit
member.summary: On datetime series, this allows for setting the pointInterval to the two irregular time units, month and year. Combine it with pointInterval to draw quarters, 6 months, 10 years etc.

member.summary: The width of each point on the x axis. For example in a column chart with one value each day, the pointRange would be 1 day (= 24 * 3600 * 1000 milliseconds). This is normally computed automatically, but this option can be used to override the automatic value.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ScatterSeries.PointStart
member.summary: If no x values are given for the points in a series, pointStart defines on what value to start. On a datetime X axis, the number will be given as milliseconds since 1970-01-01, for example Date.UTC(2011, 0, 1).

member.summary: A wrapper object for all the series options in specific states.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ScatterSeries.StickyTracking
member.summary: Sticky tracking of mouse events. When true, the mouseOut event on a series isn't triggered until the mouse moves over another series, or out of the plot area. When false, the mouseOut event on a series is triggered when the mouse leaves the area around the series' graph or markers. This also implies the tooltip. When stickyTracking is false and tooltip.shared is false, the tooltip will be hidden when moving the mouse between series.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ScatterSeries.TurboThreshold
member.summary: When a series contains a data array that is longer than this, only one dimensional arrays of numbers, or two dimensional arrays with x and y values are allowed. Also, only the first point is tested, and the rest are assumed to be the same format. This saves expensive data checking and indexing in long series. Set it to 0 disable.

summary.p: Datetime formats for the header of the tooltip in a stock chart. The format can vary within a chart depending on the currently selected time range and the current data grouping.
The default formats are:

For each of these array definitions, the first item is the format used when the active time span is one unit. For instance, if the current data applies to one week, the first item of the week array is used. The second and third items are used when the active time span is more than two units. For instance, if the current data applies to two weeks, the second and third item of the week array are used, and applied to the start and end date of the time span.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ScatterSeriesDataGrouping.Enabled
member.summary: Enable or disable data grouping. Defaults to true.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ScatterSeriesDataGrouping.Forced
member.summary: When data grouping is forced, it runs no matter how small the intervals are. This can be handy for example when the sum should be calculated for values appearing at random times within each hour. Defaults to false.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ScatterSeriesDataGrouping.GroupPixelWidth
member.summary: The approximate pixel width of each group. If for example a series with 30 points is displayed over a 600 pixel wide plot area, no grouping is performed. If however the series contains so many points that the spacing is less than the groupPixelWidth, Highcharts will try to group it into appropriate groups so that each is more or less two pixels wide. If multiple series with different group pixel widths are drawn on the same x axis, all series will take the greatest width. For example, line series have 2px default group width, while column series have 10px. If combined, both the line and the column will have 10px by default. Defaults to 2.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ScatterSeriesDataGrouping.Smoothed
member.summary: Normally, a group is indexed by the start of that group, so for example when 30 daily values are grouped into one month, that month's x value will be the 1st of the month. This apparently shifts the data to the left. When the smoothed option is true, this is compensated for. The data is shifted to the middle of the group, and min and max values are preserved. Internally, this is used in the Navigator series. Defaults to false.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ScatterSeriesDataLabels.Formatter
member.summary:
Callback JavaScript function to format the data label. Note that if a format is defined, the format takes precedence and the formatter is ignored. Available data are:
this.percentage Stacked series and pies only. The point's percentage of the total.
this.point The point object. The point name, if defined, is available through this.point.name.
this.series: The series object. The series name is available through this.series.name.
this.total Stacked series only. The total value at this point's x value.
this.x: The x value.
this.y: The y value.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ScatterSeriesDataLabels.Overflow
member.summary: How to handle data labels that flow outside the plot area. The default is justify, which aligns them inside the plot area. For columns and bars, this means it will be moved inside the bar. To display data labels outside the plot area, set crop to false and overflow to "none".

summary.p: A predefined shape or symbol for the marker. When null, the symbol is pulled from options.symbols. Other possible values are "circle", "square", "diamond", "triangle" and "triangle-down".
Additionally, the URL to a graphic can be given on this form: "url(graphic.png)". Note that for the image to be applied to exported charts, its URL needs to be accessible by the export server.
Custom callbacks for symbol path generation can also be added to Highcharts.SVGRenderer.prototype.symbols. The callback is then used by its method name, as shown in the demo.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.ScatterSeriesStatesHover.Enabled
member.summary: Enable separate styles for the hovered series to visualize that the user hovers either the series itself or the legend. Enabling it has a performance penalty as it requires that a second layer be drawn as a double buffer. This means twice as much graphics to draw for each plot, which can make a great difference for charts with a high number of series or points..

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.Series.Data
member.summary:
An array of data points for the series. The series object is expecting the points to be ordered from low to high. The reason for this is to increase performance. While in many cases the data is fetched from a server, it's also more convenient to sort on the server and thereby save on client resources. The points can be given in three ways:
A list of numerical values. In this case, the numerical values will be interpreted as y values, and x values will be automatically calculated, either starting at 0 and incrementing by 1, or from pointStart and pointInterval given in the plotOptions. This option is not available for series types with more than one value per point, like area range or OHLC. Example:data: [0, 5, 3, 5]
A list of arrays with two values. In this case, the first value is the x value and the second is the y value. If the first value is a string, it is applied as the name of the point, and the x value is incremented following the above rules.
For series with more than one value per point, like range or OHLC, the arrays will be interpreted as [x, low, high] or [x, open, high, low, close]. In these cases, the X value can be skipped altogether to make use of pointStart and pointRange. Example:data: [[5, 2], [6, 3], [8, 2]]
A list of object with named values. In this case the objects arepoint configuration objects as seen under options.point.
Range series values are given by low and high, while candlestick/OHLC values are given by open, high, low, close. Example:data: [{name: 'Point 1',color: '#00FF00',y: 0}, {name: 'Point 2',color: '#FF00FF',y: 5}]
In turbo mode, when working with series longer than turboThreshold (1000 points by default), only one- or two dimensional arrays of numbers are allowed. The first value is tested, and we assume that all the rest are defined the same way.
Note data must be sorted by X in order for the tooltip positioning and data grouping to work.

summary.p: Enable or disable the initial animation when a series is displayed. The animation can also be set as a configuration object. Please note that this option only applies to the initial animation of the series itself. For other animations, see chart.animation and the animation parameter under the API methods.The following properties are supported:

dl.dd: The duration of the animation in milliseconds.

When using jQuery as the general framework, the easing can be set to linear orswing. More easing functions are available with the use of jQuery plug-ins, most notablythe jQuery UI suite. See the jQuery docs. When using MooTools as the general framework, use the property name transition instead of easing.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.SplineSeries.CropThreshold
member.summary: When the series contains less points than the crop threshold, all points are drawn, event if the points fall outside the visible plot area at the current zoom. The advantage of drawing all points (including markers and columns), is that animation is performed on updates. On the other hand, when the series contains more points than the crop threshold, the series data is cropped to only contain points that fall within the plot area. The advantage of cropping away invisible points is to increase performance on large series. .

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.SplineSeries.GapSize
member.summary:
Defines when to display a gap in the graph. A gap size of 5 means that if the distance between two points is greater than five times that of the two closest points, the graph will be broken.
In practice, this option is most often used to visualize gaps in time series. In a stock chart, intraday data is available for daytime hours, while gaps will appear in nights and weekends..

summary.p: Datetime formats for the header of the tooltip in a stock chart. The format can vary within a chart depending on the currently selected time range and the current data grouping.
The default formats are:

For each of these array definitions, the first item is the format used when the active time span is one unit. For instance, if the current data applies to one week, the first item of the week array is used. The second and third items are used when the active time span is more than two units. For instance, if the current data applies to two weeks, the second and third item of the week array are used, and applied to the start and end date of the time span.

member.summary: Enable or disable data grouping. Defaults to true.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.SplineSeriesDataGrouping.Forced
member.summary: When data grouping is forced, it runs no matter how small the intervals are. This can be handy for example when the sum should be calculated for values appearing at random times within each hour. Defaults to false.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.SplineSeriesDataGrouping.GroupPixelWidth
member.summary: The approximate pixel width of each group. If for example a series with 30 points is displayed over a 600 pixel wide plot area, no grouping is performed. If however the series contains so many points that the spacing is less than the groupPixelWidth, Highcharts will try to group it into appropriate groups so that each is more or less two pixels wide. If multiple series with different group pixel widths are drawn on the same x axis, all series will take the greatest width. For example, line series have 2px default group width, while column series have 10px. If combined, both the line and the column will have 10px by default. Defaults to 2.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.SplineSeriesDataGrouping.Smoothed
member.summary: Normally, a group is indexed by the start of that group, so for example when 30 daily values are grouped into one month, that month's x value will be the 1st of the month. This apparently shifts the data to the left. When the smoothed option is true, this is compensated for. The data is shifted to the middle of the group, and min and max values are preserved. Internally, this is used in the Navigator series. Defaults to false.

summary.p: The HTML of the tooltip header line. Variables are enclosed by curly brackets. The point.key variable contains the category name, x value or datetime string depending on the type of axis. For datetime axes, the point.key date format can be set using tooltip.xDateFormat.

summary.p: Callback function to format the text of the tooltip from scratch. Return false to disable tooltip for a specific point on series.

A subset of HTML is supported. The HTML of the tooltip is parsed and converted to SVG, therefore this isn't a complete HTML renderer. The following tabs are supported: , , , ,
, . Spans can be styled with a style attribute, but only text-related CSS that is shared with SVG is handled.

Since version 2.1 the tooltip can be shared between multiple series through the shared option. The available data in the formatter differ a bit depending on whether the tooltip is shared or not. In a shared tooltip, all properties except x, which is common for all points, are kept in an array, this.points.
Available data are:

dl.dd: Stacked series and pies only. The point's percentage of the total.
The point object. The point name, if defined, is available through this.point.name.
In a shared tooltip, this is an array containing all other properties for each point.
The series object. The series name is available through this.series.name.
Stacked series only. The total value at this point's x value.
The x value. This property is the same regardless of the tooltip being shared or not.
The y value.

summary.p: The HTML of the tooltip header line. Variables are enclosed by curly brackets. Available variablesare point.key, series.name, series.color and other members from the point and series objects. The point.key variable contains the category name, x value or datetime string depending on the type of axis. For datetime axes, the point.key date format can be set using tooltip.xDateFormat.
Defaults to {point.key}

The HTML of the point's line in the tooltip. Variables are enclosed by curly brackets. Available variables are point.x, point.y, point.change, series.name and series.color and other properties on the same form. Furthermore, point.y can be extended by the tooltip.valuePrefix and tooltip.valueSuffix variables. This can also be overridden for each series, which makes it a good hook for displaying units.

summary.p: A callback function to place the tooltip in a default position. The callback receives three parameters: labelWidth, labelHeight and point, where point contains values for plotX and plotY telling where the reference point is in the plot area. Add chart.plotLeft and chart.plotTop to get the full coordinates.
The return should be an object containing x and y values, for example { x: 100, y: 100 }.

member.summary: When the tooltip is shared, the entire plot area will capture mouse movement or touch events. Tooltip texts for series types with ordered data (not pie, scatter, flags etc) will be shown in a single bubble. This is recommended for single series charts and for tablet/mobile optimized charts.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.Tooltip.Snap
member.summary: Proximity snap for graphs or single points. Does not apply to bars, columns and pie slices. It defaults to 10 for mouse-powered devices and 25 for touch devices. Note that since Highstock 2.1 the whole plot area by default captures pointer events in order to show the tooltip, so for tooltip.snap to make sense, stickyTracking must be false.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.Tooltip.Style
member.summary: CSS styles for the tooltip. The tooltip can also be styled through the CSS class .highcharts-tooltip. Default value:style: {color: '#333333',fontSize: '12px',padding: '8px'}

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.Tooltip.UseHTML
member.summary: Use HTML to render the contents of the tooltip instead of SVG. Using HTML allows advanced formatting like tables and images in the tooltip. It is also recommended for rtl languages as it works around rtl bugs in early Firefox.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.Tooltip.ValueDecimals
member.summary: How many decimals to show in each series' y value. This is overridable in each series' tooltip options object. The default is to preserve all decimals.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.Tooltip.ValuePrefix
member.summary: A string to prepend to each series' y value. Overridable in each series' tooltip options object.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.Tooltip.ValueSuffix
member.summary: A string to append to each series' y value. Overridable in each series' tooltip options object.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.Tooltip.XDateFormat
member.summary: The format for the date in the tooltip header. If data grouping is used, the default is a smart guess based on how close the closest points are. It is pulled from the #plotOptions.dataGrouping.dateTimeLabelFormats array.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.XAxis.AllowDecimals

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.XAxis.Max
member.summary: The maximum value of the axis. If null, the max value is automatically calculated. If the endOnTick option is true, the max value might be rounded up. The actual maximum value is also influenced by chart.alignTicks.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.XAxis.MaxPadding
member.summary: Padding of the max value relative to the length of the axis. A padding of 0.05 will make a 100px axis 5px longer. This is useful when you don't want the highest data value to appear on the edge of the plot area. When the axis' max option is set or a max extreme is set using axis.setExtremes(), the maxPadding will be ignored.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.XAxis.Min
member.summary: The minimum value of the axis. If null the min value is automatically calculated. If the startOnTick option is true, the min value might be rounded down.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.XAxis.MinPadding
member.summary: Padding of the min value relative to the length of the axis. A padding of 0.05 will make a 100px axis 5px longer. This is useful when you don't want the lowest data value to appear on the edge of the plot area. When the axis' min option is set or a min extreme is set using axis.setExtremes(), the minPadding will be ignored.

summary.p: The minimum range to display. The entire axis will not be allowed to span over a smaller interval than this. For example, for a datetime axis the main unit is milliseconds. If minRange is set to 3600000, you can't zoom in more than to one hour.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.XAxis.MinTickInterval
member.summary: The minimum tick interval allowed in axis values. For example on zooming in on an axis with daily data, this can be used to prevent the axis from showing hours. Defaults to the closest distance between two points on the axis.

member.summary: The distance in pixels from the plot area to the axis line. A positive offset moves the axis with it's line, labels and ticks away from the plot area. This is typically used when two or more axes are displayed on the same side of the plot.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.XAxis.Opposite
member.summary: Whether to display the axis on the opposite side of the normal. The normal is on the left side for vertical axes and bottom for horizontal, so the opposite sides will be right and top respectively. This is typically used with dual or multiple axes.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.XAxis.Ordinal
member.summary: In an ordinal axis, the points are equally spaced in the chart regardless of the actual time or x distance between them. This means that missing data for nights or weekends will not take up space in the chart.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.XAxis.PlotLines

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.XAxis.Reversed
member.summary: Whether to reverse the axis so that the highest number is closest to the origin.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.XAxis.ShowEmpty
member.summary: Whether to show the axis line and title when the axis has no data.

member.summary: Whether to show the last tick label.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.XAxis.StartOfWeek
member.summary: For datetime axes, this decides where to put the tick between weeks. 0 = Sunday, 1 = Monday.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.XAxis.StartOnTick
member.summary: Whether to force the axis to start on a tick. Use this option with the minPadding option to control the axis start. In Highstock, startOnTick is allways false when the navigator is enabled, to prevent jumpy scrolling.

summary.p: The amount of ticks to draw on the axis. This opens up for aligning the ticks of multiple charts or panes within a chart. This option overrides the tickPixelInterval option.
This option only has an effect on linear axes. Datetime, logarithmic or category axes are not affected.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.XAxis.TickColor
member.summary: Color for the main tick marks.

summary.p: The interval of the tick marks in axis units. When null, the tick interval is computed to approximately follow the tickPixelInterval on linear and datetime axes. On categorized axes, a null tickInterval will default to 1, one category. Note that datetime axes are based on milliseconds, so for example an interval of one day is expressed as 24 * 3600 * 1000.
If the tickInterval is too dense for labels to be drawn, Highcharts may remove ticks.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.XAxis.TickLength
member.summary: The pixel length of the main tick marks.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.XAxis.TickPixelInterval
member.summary: If tickInterval is null this option sets the approximate pixel interval of the tick marks. Not applicable to categorized axis. Defaults to 72 for the Y axis and 100 forthe X axis.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.XAxis.TickPosition
member.summary: The position of the major tick marks relative to the axis line. Can be one of inside and outside.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.XAxis.TickPositioner
member.summary: A callback function to compute on what values the ticks should be placed. Returns an array of numbers. The min and max of the axis are passed in as the first and second parameter. Options like tickInterval can be accessed by this.options.tickInterval. The automatic tick positions are accessible through this.tickPositions and can be modified by the callback.Note that in stock charts, the last label is hidden by default by the showLastLabel option.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.XAxis.TickPositions
member.summary: A collection of hard coded tick value positions. This overrides the auto computed positions based on tickInterval and tickPixelInterval. See also tickPositioner.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.XAxis.TickWidth
member.summary: The pixel width of the major tick marks.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.XAxisBreaks.To

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.XAxisEvents.AfterSetExtremes
member.summary: As opposed to the setExtremes event, this event fires after the final min and max values are computed and corrected for minRange.

summary.p: Fires when the minimum and maximum is set for the axis, either by calling the .setExtremes() method or by selecting an area in the chart. One parameter, event, is passed to the function. This contains common event information based on jQuery or MooTools depending on which library is used as the base for Highcharts.

The new user set minimum and maximum values can be found by event.min and event.max. When an axis is zoomed all the way out from the "Reset zoom" button, event.min and event.max are null, and the new extremes are set based on this.dataMin and this.dataMax.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.XAxisLabels.Align
member.summary: What part of the string the given position is anchored to. Can be one of "left", "center" or "right". Defaults to an intelligent guess based on which side of the chart the axis is on and the rotation of the label.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.XAxisLabels.AutoRotation
member.summary: For horizontal axes, the allowed degrees of label rotation to prevent overlapping labels. If there is enough space, labels are not rotated. As the chart gets narrower, it will start rotating the labels -45 degrees, then remove every second label and try again with rotations 0 and -45 etc. Set it to false to disable rotation, which will cause the labels to word-wrap if possible.

member.summary: The minimum tick interval allowed in axis values. For example on zooming in on an axis with daily data, this can be used to prevent the axis from showing hours. Defaults to the closest distance between two points on the axis.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.YAxis.MinorGridLineColor
member.summary: Color of the minor, secondary grid lines.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.YAxis.MinorTickColor
member.summary: Color for the minor tick marks.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.YAxis.MinorTickLength
member.summary: The pixel length of the minor tick marks.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.YAxis.MinorTickPosition

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.YAxis.MinorTickWidth

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.YAxis.Offset
member.summary: The distance in pixels from the plot area to the axis line. A positive offset moves the axis with it's line, labels and ticks away from the plot area. This is typically used when two or more axes are displayed on the same side of the plot.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.YAxis.Opposite
member.summary: Whether to display the axis on the opposite side of the normal. The normal is on the left side for vertical axes and bottom for horizontal, so the opposite sides will be right and top respectively. In Highstock 1.x, the Y axis was placed on the left side by default.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.YAxis.Ordinal
member.summary: In an ordinal axis, the points are equally spaced in the chart regardless of the actual time or x distance between them. This means that missing data for nights or weekends will not take up space in the chart.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.YAxis.PlotBands
member.summary: An array of objects defining plot bands on the Y axis.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.YAxis.PlotLines
member.summary: An array of lines stretching across the plot area, marking a specific value on one of the axes.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.YAxis.Range
member.summary: The zoomed range to display when only defining one or none of min or max. For example, to show the latest month, a range of one month can be set.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.YAxis.Reversed
member.summary: Whether to reverse the axis so that the highest number is closest to the origin.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.YAxis.ReversedStacks
member.summary: If true, the first series in a stack will be drawn on top in a positive, non-reversed Y axis. If false, the first series is in the base of the stack.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.YAxis.ShowEmpty
member.summary: Whether to show the axis line and title when the axis has no data.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.YAxis.ShowFirstLabel

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.YAxis.ShowLastLabel
member.summary: Whether to show the last tick label.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.YAxis.StartOfWeek
member.summary: For datetime axes, this decides where to put the tick between weeks. 0 = Sunday, 1 = Monday.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.YAxis.StartOnTick
member.summary: Whether to force the axis to start on a tick. Use this option with the maxPadding option to control the axis start.

summary.p: The amount of ticks to draw on the axis. This opens up for aligning the ticks of multiple charts or panes within a chart. This option overrides the tickPixelInterval option.
This option only has an effect on linear axes. Datetime, logarithmic or category axes are not affected.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.YAxis.TickColor
member.summary: Color for the main tick marks.

summary.p: The interval of the tick marks in axis units. When null, the tick interval is computed to approximately follow the tickPixelInterval on linear and datetime axes. On categorized axes, a null tickInterval will default to 1, one category. Note that datetime axes are based on milliseconds, so for example an interval of one day is expressed as 24 * 3600 * 1000.
If the tickInterval is too dense for labels to be drawn, Highcharts may remove ticks.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.YAxis.TickLength
member.summary: The pixel length of the main tick marks.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.YAxis.TickPixelInterval
member.summary: If tickInterval is null this option sets the approximate pixel interval of the tick marks. Not applicable to categorized axis. Defaults to 72 for the Y axis and 100 forthe X axis.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.YAxis.TickPosition
member.summary: The position of the major tick marks relative to the axis line. Can be one of inside and outside.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.YAxis.TickPositioner
member.summary: A callback function to compute on what values the ticks should be placed. Returns an array of numbers. The min and max of the axis are passed in as the first and second parameter. Options like tickInterval can be accessed by this.options.tickInterval. The automatic tick positions are accessible through this.tickPositions and can be modified by the callback.Note that in stock charts, the last label is hidden by default by the showLastLabel option.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.YAxis.TickPositions
member.summary: A collection of hard coded tick value positions. This overrides the auto computed positions based on tickInterval and tickPixelInterval. See also tickPositioner.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.YAxis.TickWidth
member.summary: The pixel width of the major tick marks.

summary.p: The top position of the Y axis. If it's a number, it is interpreted as pixel position relative to the chart.
Since Highstock 2: If it's a percentage string, it is interpreted as percentages of the plot height, offset from plot area top.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.YAxisBreaks.BreakSize
member.summary: A number indicating how much space should be left between the start and the end of the break. The break size is given in axis units, so for instance on a datetime axis, a break size of 3600000 would indicate the equivalent of an hour.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.YAxisBreaks.From
member.summary: The point where the break starts.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.YAxisBreaks.Repeat
member.summary: Defines an interval after which the break appears again. By default the breaks do not repeat.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.YAxisBreaks.To
member.summary: The point where the break ends.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.YAxisEvents.AfterSetExtremes
member.summary: As opposed to the setExtremes event, this event fires after the final min and max values are computed and corrected for minRange.

summary.p: Fires when the minimum and maximum is set for the axis, either by calling the .setExtremes() method or by selecting an area in the chart. One parameter, event, is passed to the function. This contains common event information based on jQuery or MooTools depending on which library is used as the base for Highcharts.

The new user set minimum and maximum values can be found by event.min and event.max. When an axis is zoomed all the way out from the "Reset zoom" button, event.min and event.max are null, and the new extremes are set based on this.dataMin and this.dataMax.

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.YAxisLabels.Align

member.name: P:Highsoft.Web.Mvc.Stocks.YAxisLabels.AutoRotation
member.summary: For horizontal axes, the allowed degrees of label rotation to prevent overlapping labels. If there is enough space, labels are not rotated. As the chart gets narrower, it will start rotating the labels -45 degrees, then remove every second label and try again with rotations 0 and -45 etc. Set it to false to disable rotation, which will cause the labels to word-wrap if possible.
